<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000150.tif">

<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="[1]">
<HEAD>The Babees Book, OR A 'LYTYL REPORTE' OF HOW YOUNG PEOPLE SHOULD BEHAVE. [<I>MS. Harl.</I> 5086, <I>fol.</I> 86-90; <I>ab.</I> 1475 A.D.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN this tretys the whiche I thenke to wryte</L>
<L>Out of latyn in-to my comvne langage,</L>
<L>He me supporte (sen I kan nat endyte),</L>
<L N="4">The whiche only after his owne ymage</L>
<L>Fourmyd man-kynde! For alle of tendre age</L>
<L>In curtesye Resseyve shulle document,</L>
<L>And vertues knowe, by this lytil coment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And Facett seythe the Book of curtesye,</L>
<L N="9">Vertues to knowe, thaym forto haue and vse,</L>
<L>Is thing moste heelfulle in this worlde trevly.</L>
<L>Therfore in feythe I wole me nat excuse</L>
<L N="12">From this labour ywys, nor hit Refuse;</L>
<L>For myn owne lernynge wole I say summe thing</L>
<L>That touchis vertues and curtesye havyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But, O yonge Babees, whome bloode Royalle</L>
<L N="16">Withe grace, feture, and hyhe habylite</L>
<L>Hathe enourmyd, on yow ys that I calle</L>
<L>To knowe this Book; for it were grete pyte,</L>
<L>Syn that in yow ys sette sovereyne beaute,</L>
<L N="20">But yf vertue and nurture were withe alle;</L>
<L>To yow therfore I speke in specyalle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And nouhte to hem of elde that bene experte</L>
<L>In governaunce, nurture, and honeste.
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="2"></L>
<L N="24">For what nedys to yeve helle peynes smerte,</L>
<L>Ioye vnto hevene, or water vnto the see,</L>
<L>Heete to the fyre that kan nat but hoote be?<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It nedys nouhte: therfore, O Babees yynge,</L>
<L N="28">My Book only is made for youre lernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Therfore I pray that no man Reprehende</L>
<L>This lytyl Book, the whiche for yow I make;</L>
<L>But where defaute ys, latte ylke man amende,</L>
<L N="32">And nouhte deme yt; [I] pray thaym for youre sake.</L>
<L>For other mede ywys I kepe noone take</L>
<L>But that god wolde this Book myhte yche man plese,</L>
<L>And in lernynge vnto you donne somme ese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Eke, swete children, yf there be eny worde</L>
<L N="37">That yee kenne nouhte, spyrre whils yee yt ken;</L>
<L>Whanne yee yt knowe, yee mowe holde yt in horde,</L>
<L>Thus thurhe spyrryng yee mowe lerne at wyse men.</L>
<L N="40">Also thenke nouhte to straungely at my penne,</L>
<L>In this metre for yow lyste to procede,</L>
<L>Men vsen yt; therfore on hit take hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But amonge alle that I thenke of to telle,</L>
<L N="44">My purpos ys first only forto trete</L>
<L>How yee Babees in housholde that done duelle</L>
<L>Shulde haue youre sylf whenne yee be sette at mete,</L>
<L>And how yee shulde whenne men lyste yow Re|hete,</L>
<L N="48">Haue wordes lovly, swete, bleste, and benyngne.</L>
<L>In this helpe me O Marie, Modir dyngne!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And eke, o lady myn, Facecia!</L>
<L>My penne thow guyde, and helpe vnto me shewe;
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="3"></L>
<L N="52">For as the firste off alle lettres ys the A,<MILESTONE N="87a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>So Artow firste Modir of alle vertue.</L>
<L>Off myn vnkunnynge, swete lady, now Rewe;</L>
<L>And thouhe vntauhte I speke of governaunce,</L>
<L N="56">Withe thy swete helpe supporte myn ygnor|aunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>A,</B> Bele Babees, herkne now to my lore!</L>
<L>Whenne yee entre into your lordis place,</L>
<L>Say first, "god spede;" And alle that ben by|fore</L>
<L N="60">Yow in this stede, salue withe humble Face;</L>
<L>Stert nat Rudely; komme Inne an esy pace;</L>
<L>Holde vp youre heede, and knele but on oone kne</L>
<L>To youre sovereyne or lorde, whedir he be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">&para; And yf they speke withe you at youre komynge,</L>
<L>Withe stable Eye loke vpone theym Rihte,</L>
<L>To theyre tales and yeve yee goode herynge</L>
<L>Whils they haue seyde; loke eke withe your myhte</L>
<L N="68">Yee Iangle nouhte, also caste nouhte your syhte</L>
<L>Aboute the hovs, but take to theym entent</L>
<L>Withe blythe vysage, and spiryt diligent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whenne yee Answere or speke, yee shulle be purveyde</L>
<L N="72">What yee shalle say / speke eke thing fructuous;</L>
<L>On esy wyse latte thy Resone be sayde</L>
<L>In wordes gentylle and also compendious,<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For many wordes ben rihte Tedious</L>
<L N="76">To ylke wyseman that shalle yeve audience;</L>
<L>Thaym to eschewe therfore doo diligence.
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="4"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Take eke noo seete, but to stonde be yee preste;</L>
<L>Whils forto sytte ye haue in komaundement,</L>
<L N="80">Youre heede, youre hande, your feet, holde yee in reste;</L>
<L>Nor thurhe clowyng your flesshe loke yee nat Rent;</L>
<L>Lene to no poste whils that ye stande present</L>
<L>Byfore your lorde, nor handylle ye no thyng</L>
<L N="84">Als for that tyme vnto the hovs touching.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; At euery tyme obeye vnto youre lorde</L>
<L>Whenne yee answere, ellis stonde yee styl as stone</L>
<L>But yf he speke; loke withe oon accorde</L>
<L N="88">That yf yee se komme Inne eny persone</L>
<L>Better thanne yee, that yee goo bak anoone</L>
<L>And gyff him place; youre bak eke in no way</L>
<L>Turne on no wihte, as ferforthe as ye may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="92">&para; Yiff that youre lorde also yee se drynkynge,</L>
<L>Looke that ye be in rihte stable sylence</L>
<L>Withe-oute lowde lauhtere or Iangelynge,</L>
<L>Rovnynge, Iapynge, or other Insolence.</L>
<L N="96">Yiff he komaunde also in his presence</L>
<L>Yow forto sytte, fulfille his wylle belyve,</L>
<L>And for youre seete, looke nat withe other stryve,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whenne yee er sette, take noone vnhoneste tale;</L>
<L N="100">Eke forto skorne eschewe withe alle your myhte;</L>
<L>Latte ay youre chere be lowly, blythe, and hale,<MILESTONE N="88a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Withe-oute chidynge as that yee wolde fyhte.</L>
<L>Yiff yee perceyve also that eny wihte</L>
<L N="104">Lyst you kommende that better be thanne yee,</L>
<L>Ryse vp anoone, and thanke him withe herte free.
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="5"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Yif that yee se youre lorde or youre lady</L>
<L>Touching the housholde speke of eny thinge,</L>
<L N="108">Latt theym alloone, for that is curtesy,</L>
<L>And entremete yow nouhte of theyre doynge,</L>
<L>But be Ay Redy withe-oute feynynge</L>
<L>At hable tyme to done your lorde service,</L>
<L N="112">So shalle yee gete anoone a name of price.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Also to brynge drynke, holde lihte whanne tyme ys,</L>
<L>Or to doo that whiche ouhte forto be done,</L>
<L>Looke yee be preste, for so yee shalle ywys</L>
<L N="116">In nurture gete a gentyl name ful sone;</L>
<L>And yif ye shulde at god aske yow a bone,</L>
<L>Als to the worlde better in noo degre</L>
<L>Mihte yee desire thanne nurtred forto be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Yif that youre lorde his owne coppe lyste com|mende</L>
<L N="121">To yow to drynke, ryse vp whanne yee it take,</L>
<L>And resseyve it goodly withe boothe youre hende;</L>
<L>Of yt also to noone other profre ye make,</L>
<L N="124">But vnto him that brouhte yt yee hit take</L>
<L>Whenne yee haue done, for yt in no kyn wyse<MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Auhte comvne be, as techis vs the wyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now must I telle in shorte, for I muste so,</L>
<L N="128">Youre observaunce that ye shalle done at none;</L>
<L>Whenne that ye se youre lorde to mete shalle goo,</L>
<L>Be redy to fecche him water sone,</L>
<L>Summe helle water; summe holde to he hathe done</L>
<L N="132">The clothe to him, And from him yee nat pace</L>
<L>Whils he be sette, and haue herde sayde the grace.
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="6"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Byfore him stonde whils he komaunde yow sytte,</L>
<L>Withe clene handes Ay Redy him to serve;</L>
<L N="136">Whenne yee be sette, your knyf withe alle your wytte</L>
<L>Vnto youre sylf bothe clene and sharpe con|serve,</L>
<L>That honestly yee mowe your own mete kerve.</L>
<L>Latte curtesye and sylence withe yow duelle,</L>
<L N="140">And foule tales looke noone to other telle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Kutte withe your knyf your brede, and breke yt nouhte;</L>
<L>A clene Trenchour byfore yow eke ye lay,</L>
<L>And whenne your potage to yow shalle be brouhte,</L>
<L N="144">Take yow sponys, and soupe by no way,</L>
<L>And in youre dysshe leve nat your spone, I pray,</L>
<L>Nor on the borde lenynge be yee nat sene,</L>
<L>But from embrowyng the clothe yee kepe clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oute ouere youre dysshe your heede yee nat hynge,</L>
<L N="149">And withe fulle mouthe drynke in no wyse;</L>
<L>Youre nose, your teethe, your naylles, from pykynge,</L>
<L>Kepe At your mete, for so techis the wyse.</L>
<L N="152">Eke or ye take in youre mouthe, yow avyse,</L>
<L>So mekyl mete but that yee rihte welle mowe</L>
<L>Answere, And speke, whenne men speke to yow.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne ye shalle drynke, your mouthe clence withe A clothe;</L>
<L N="156">Youre handes eke that they in no manere</L>
<L>Imbrowe the cuppe, for thanne shulle noone be lothe
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Withe yow to drynke that ben withe yow yfere.</L>
<L>The salte also touche nat in his salere</L>
<L N="160">Withe nokyns mete, but lay it honestly</L>
<L>On youre Trenchoure, for that is curtesy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Youre knyf withe mete to your mouthe nat bere,</L>
<L>And in youre hande nor holden yee yt no way,</L>
<L N="164">Eke yf to yow be brouhte goode metys sere,</L>
<L>Luke curteysly of ylke mete yee assay,</L>
<L>And yf your dysshe withe mete be tane away</L>
<L>And better brouhte, curtesye wole certeyne</L>
<L N="168">Yee late yt passe and calle it nat ageyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And yf straungers withe yow be sette at mete,</L>
<L>And vnto yow goode mete be brouhte or sente,</L>
<L>Withe parte of hit goodely yee theym Rehete,</L>
<L N="172">For yt ys nouhte ywys convenyent,</L>
<L>Withe yow at mete whanne other ben present,</L>
<L>Alle forto holde that vnto yow ys brouhte,</L>
<L>And as wrecches on other vouchesauf nouhte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Kutte nouhte youre mete eke as it were Felde men,<MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="177">That to theyre mete haue suche an appetyte</L>
<L>That they ne rekke in what wyse, where ne when,</L>
<L>Nor how vngoodly they on theyre mete twyte;</L>
<L N="180">But, swete children, haue al-wey your delyte</L>
<L>In curtesye, and in verrey gentylnesse,</L>
<L>And at youre myhte eschewe boystousnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne chese ys brouhte, A Trenchoure ha ye clene</L>
<L N="184">On whiche withe clene knyf [ye] your chese mowe kerve;</L>
<L>In youre fedynge luke goodly yee be sene,
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>And from Iangelyng your tunge al-wey conserve,</L>
<L>For so ywys yee shalle a name deserve</L>
<L N="188">Off gentylnesse and of goode governaunce,</L>
<L>And in vertue al-wey youre silf avaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne that so ys that ende shalle kome of mete,</L>
<L>Youre knyffes clene, where they ouhte to be,</L>
<L N="192">Luke yee putte vppe; and holde eke yee your seete</L>
<L>Whils yee haue wasshe, for so wole honeste.</L>
<L>Whenne yee haue done, looke thanne goodly that yee</L>
<L>Withe-oute lauhtere, Iapynge, or boystous worde,</L>
<L N="196">Ryse vppe, and goo vnto youre lordis borde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And stonde yee there, and passe yee him nat fro</L>
<L>Whils grace ys sayde and brouhte vnto an ende,</L>
<L>Thanne somme of yow for water owe to goo,</L>
<L N="200">Somme holde the clothe, somme poure vppon his hende.</L>
<L>Other service thanne this I myhte comende<MILESTONE N="90a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To yow to done, but, for the tyme is shorte,</L>
<L>I putte theym nouhte in this lytyl Reporte,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But ouere I passe, prayyng withe spyrit gladde</L>
<L N="205">Of this labour that no wihte me detray,</L>
<L>But where to lytyl ys, latte him more adde,</L>
<L>And whenne to myche ys, latte him take away;</L>
<L N="208">For thouhe I wolde, tyme wole that I no more say;</L>
<L>I leve therfore, And this Book I directe</L>
<L>To euery wihte that lyste yt to correcte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And, swete children, for whos love now I write,</L>
<L N="212">I yow beseche withe verrey lovande herte,
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>To knowe this book that yee sette your delyte;</L>
<L>And myhtefulle god, that suffred peynes smerte,</L>
<L>In curtesye he make yow so experte,</L>
<L N="216">That thurhe your nurture and youre governaunce</L>
<L>In lastynge blysse yee mowe your self auaunce!</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>&para; Lerne or be Lewde.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Amerous, to Aunterous, ne Angre the nat to to muche;<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To Bolde, ne to Besy, ne Bourde nat to large;</L>
<L>To Curteys, to Cruelle, ne Care nat to sore;</L>
<L N="4">To Dulle, ne to Dredefulle, ne Drynke nat to offte;</L>
<L>To Elenge, to Excellent, ne to Carefulle ney|thur;</L>
<L>To Fers, ne to Famuler, but Frendely of Chere;</L>
<L>To gladde, ne to Glorious, and Gelousy thow hate;</L>
<L N="8">To Hasty, to Hardy, ne to Hevy in thyn Herte;</L>
<L>To Iettyng, ne to Iangelyng, and Iape nat to ofte;</L>
<L>To Kynde, ne to Kepyng, and warre Knavis cacches;</L>
<L>To Lothe, ne to Lovyng, ne to Lyberalle of goode;</L>
<L N="12">To Medlous, to Mury, but as goode Maner askithe;</L>
<L>To noyous, ne to Nyce, ne to Newfangylle;</L>
<L>To Orped, to Overtwert, and Othes, sir, thow hate;
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>To Preysyng, to Preve withe Prynces and Dukes;</L>
<L N="16">To Queynt, to Querelous, and Queme welle thy maistre;</L>
<L>To Riotous, to Revelyng, ne Rage nat to muche;</L>
<L>To Straunge, ne to Steryng, ne Stare nat abroode;</L>
<L>To Toyllous, to Talevys, for Temperaunce it hatithe;</L>
<L N="20">To Vengable, to Envious, and waste nat to muche;</L>
<L>To Wylde, to Wrathefulle, and Wade nat to depe;</L>
<L>A Mesurable Mene way ys beste for vs alle;<NOTE PLACE="end">[A Dietary given 'vnto Kyng Herry the v<SUP>te</SUP> by Sigismounde, Emperour of Rome,' follows.] <I>A complete copy of the A B C Alliterative Poem of which the foregoing</I> LERNE OR BE LEWDE <I>is a fragment, occurs in the Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>and is therefore added here.</I></NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>&para; YITTE LERNE OR BE LEWDE.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000161.tif" N="11">
<HEAD>The A B C of Aristotle. [<I>Lambeth</I> MS. 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 30, <I>written without breaks.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who-so wilne&thorn; to be wijs, &amp; worschip desiri&thorn;,</L>
<L>Lerne he oo lettir, &amp; looke on anothir</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e .a. b. c. of aristotil: argue not a&yogh;en &thorn;at:</L>
<L N="4">It is councel for ri&yogh;t manye clerkis &amp; kny&yogh;tis a &thorn;ousand,</L>
<L>And eek it my&yogh;te ameende a man ful ofte</L>
<L>For to leerne lore of oo lettir, &amp; his lijf saue;</L>
<L N="8">For to myche of ony &thorn;ing was neuere holsum.</L>
<L>Reede ofte on &thorn;is rolle, &amp; rewle &thorn;ou &thorn;er aftir;</L>
<L>Who-so be greued in his goost, gouerne him bettir;</L>
<L>Blame he not &thorn;e barn &thorn;at &thorn;is .a. b. c. made,</L>
<L N="12">But wite he his wickid will &amp; his werk aftir;</L>
<L>It schal neuere greue a good man &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e gilti be meendid.</L>
<L>Now herkene&thorn; &amp; heeri&thorn; how y bigynne.</L>
</LG>
<LIST>
<LABEL><B>A</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to amerose, to aunterose, ne argue not to myche.<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="page"></ITEM>
<LABEL><B>B</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to bolde, ne to bisi, ne boorde not to large.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>C</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to curteis, to cruel, ne care not to sore.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>D</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to dul, ne to dreedful, ne drinke not to ofte.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>E</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to elenge, ne to excellent, ne to eernesful nei&thorn;er.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>F</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to fers, ne to famuler, but freendli of cheere.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>G</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to glad, ne to gloriose, &amp; gelosie &thorn;ou hate.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="12"></ITEM>
<LABEL><B>H</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to hasti, ne to hardi, ne to heuy in &thorn;ine herte.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>I</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to iettynge, ne to iangelinge, ne iape not to ofte.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>K</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to kinde, ne to kepynge, &amp; be waar of knaue tacchis.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>L</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to looth for to leene, ne to liberal of goodis.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>M</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to medelus, ne to myrie, but as mesure wole it meeue.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>N</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to noiose, ne to nyce, ne use no new iettis.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>O</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to orped, ne to ouer&thorn;wart, &amp; oo&thorn;is &thorn;ou hate.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>P</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to presing, ne to preuy with princis ne with dukis;</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>Q</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to queynte, ne <MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="page">to quarelose, but queeme weel &yogh;oure souereyns.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>R</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to riotus, to reueling, ne rage not to rudeli.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>S</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to straunge, ne to stirynge, ne straungeli to stare.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>T</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to toilose, ne to talewijs, for temperaunce is beest.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>V</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to venemose, ne to veniable, &amp; voide al vilonye.</ITEM>
<LABEL><B>W</B></LABEL>
<ITEM>to wielde, ne to wra&thorn;ful, nei&thorn;er waaste, ne waade not to depe,</ITEM>
</LIST>
<P>&para; For a mesurable meene is euere &thorn;e beste of alle.<NOTE PLACE="end">["Whi is &thorn;is world biloued" follows.]</NOTE>
</P>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000163.tif" N="13">
<HEAD>Vrbanitatis.<NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>Fol.</I> 86, <I>col.</I> 2, <I>MS. Cott. Calig. A.</I> II., <I>ab.</I> 1460 A.D.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who-so wylle of nurtur lere,</L>
<L>Herken to me &amp; &yogh;e shalle here.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou comeste be-fore a lorde</L>
<L N="4">In halle, yn bowre, or at &thorn;e borde,</L>
<L>Hoode or kappe &thorn;ou of &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Ere &thorn;ou come hym alle vn-to,</L>
<L>Twyse or &thorn;ryse with-owten dowte</L>
<L N="8">To &thorn;at lorde &thorn;ou moste lowte,</L>
<L>With &thorn;y Ry&yogh;th kne lette hit be do,</L>
<L>Thy worshyp &thorn;ou mayst saue so.</L>
<L>Holde of &thorn;y cappe &amp; &thorn;y hood also</L>
<L N="12">Tylle &thorn;ou be byden hit on to do;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e whyle &thorn;ou spekest with hym,</L>
<L>Fayr &amp; louely holde vp &thorn;y chynn,</L>
<L>So aftur &thorn;e nurtur of &thorn;e book</L>
<L N="16">In his face louely &thorn;ou loke;</L>
<L>Foot &amp; hond &thorn;ou kepe fulle stylle</L>
<L>Fro clawyng or tryppyng, hit ys skylle;</L>
<L>Fro spettyng &amp; snetyng kepe &thorn;e also;</L>
<L N="20">Be priuy of voydance, &amp; lette hit go.</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou be wyse &amp; felle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto also &thorn;at &thorn;ow gouerne &thorn;e welle.</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e halle when &thorn;ou dost wende</L>
<L N="24">Amonge &thorn;e genteles gode &amp; hende,</L>
<L>Prece &thorn;ou not vp to hy&yogh; for no &thorn;yng,</L>
<L>Nor for &thorn;y hy&yogh; blood, nere for &thorn;y konnyng,</L>
<L>No&thorn;ur to sytte, ne&thorn;ur to lene,</L>
<L N="28">For hit ys ney&thorn;ur good ne clene.
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>Lette not &thorn;y contynaunce also abate,</L>
<L>For good nurtur wylle saue &thorn;y state;</L>
<L>Fadyr &amp; modyr, what euur &thorn;ey be,</L>
<L N="32">Welle ys &thorn;e chylde &thorn;at may the:</L>
<L>In halle, in chambur, ore where &thorn;ou gon,</L>
<L>Nurtur &amp; good maners make&thorn; man.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e nexte degre loke &thorn;ou wysely</L>
<L N="36">To do hem Reuerence by and by:</L>
<L>Do hem no Reuerens, but sette alle in Rowe</L>
<L>But &yogh;yf &thorn;ou &thorn;e bettur do hym knowe.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e mete when &thorn;ou art sette,</L>
<L N="40">Fayre &amp; honestly thow ete hyt:<MILESTONE N="86b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fyrste loke &thorn;at &thorn;y handes be clene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;y knyf be sharpe &amp; kene;</L>
<L>And cutte &thorn;y breed &amp; alle &thorn;y mete</L>
<L N="44">Ry&yogh;th euen as &thorn;ou doste hit ete.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou sytte be a worthyor man</L>
<L>Then &thorn;y self thow art on,</L>
<L>Suffre hym fyrste to towche &thorn;e mete</L>
<L N="48">Ere &thorn;y self any &thorn;er-of gete;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e beste morselle &thorn;ou may not stryke</L>
<L>Thow&yogh; &thorn;ou neuur so welle hit lyke.</L>
<L>Also kepe &thorn;y hondys fayre &amp; welle</L>
<L N="52">Fro fylynge of the towelle,</L>
<L>Ther-on &thorn;ou shalt not &thorn;y nose wype;</L>
<L>No&thorn;ur at &thorn;y mete &thorn;y toth &thorn;ou pyke;</L>
<L>To depe in &thorn;y cuppe &thorn;ou may not synke</L>
<L N="56">Thow&yogh; &thorn;ou haue good wylle to drynke,</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;y eyen water &thorn;ere by,</L>
<L>Then ys hyt no curtesy.</L>
<L>Loke yn &thorn;y mowth be no mete</L>
<L N="60">When &thorn;ou begynneste to drynke or speke;</L>
<L>Also when &thorn;ou sest any man drynkyng</L>
<L>That taketh hede of &thorn;y karpyng,</L>
<L>Soone a-non &thorn;ou sece &thorn;y tale,</L>
<L N="64">Whe&thorn;ur he drynke wyne or Ale.
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>Loke also &thorn;ou skorne no mon</L>
<L>In what &thorn;egre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Marg. has <I>gre</I> for insertion.]</NOTE> &thorn;ou se hym gon;</L>
<L>Nor &thorn;ou shalte no mon repreue</L>
<L N="68">&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou wylt &thorn;y owen worshyp saue,</L>
<L>For suche wordys &thorn;ou my&yogh;th out kaste</L>
<L>Sholde make &thorn;e to lyue in euelle reste;</L>
<L>Close &thorn;yn honde yn &thorn;y feste,</L>
<L N="72">And kepe &thorn;e welle from hadde-y-wyste.</L>
<L>In chambur among ladyes bry&yogh;th,<MILESTONE N="86b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Kepe &thorn;y tonge &amp; spende &thorn;y sy&yogh;th;</L>
<L>Law&yogh;e &thorn;ou not with no grette cry,</L>
<L N="76">Ne Rage &thorn;ou not with Rybawdry.</L>
<L>Pley &thorn;ou not but with &thorn;y peres;</L>
<L>Ne telle &thorn;ou not &thorn;at &thorn;ou heres,</L>
<L>Nor dyskeuere &thorn;ou not<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>not</I> put in by a later hand.]</NOTE> &thorn;yn owen dede</L>
<L N="80">For no myrth nor for no mede;</L>
<L>With fayr speche &thorn;ou may haue &thorn;y wylle,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;y speche &thorn;ou may &thorn;e spylle.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ou suwe a wordyer mon</L>
<L N="84">Then &thorn;y self &thorn;ou art on,</L>
<L>Lette &thorn;y Ry&yogh;th sholdur folow his bakke,</L>
<L>For nurtur &thorn;at ys, with-owten lakke.</L>
<L>When he doth speke, holde &thorn;e style;</L>
<L N="88">When he hath don, say &thorn;y wylle;</L>
<L>Loke yn &thorn;y speche &thorn;ou be felle,</L>
<L>And what &thorn;ou sayste a-vyse &thorn;e welle;</L>
<L>And be-refe &thorn;ou no mon his tale,</L>
<L N="92">No&thorn;ur at wyne nere at Ale.</L>
<L>Now, criste of his grette grace</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue vs alle bothe wytte &amp; space</L>
<L>Welle &thorn;is to knowe &amp; Rede,</L>
<L N="96">And heuen to haue for our mede!</L>
<L>Amen, Amen, so moot hit be,</L>
<L>So saye we alle for charyte!</L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT TRACTUS VRBANITATIS.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000166.tif" N="16">
<HEAD>The Lytylle Childrenes Lytil Boke or Edyllys be.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>[<I>Harl. MS.</I> 541, <I>fol.</I> 210; <I>and Egerton MS.</I> 1995; <I>ab.</I> 1480 A.D.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lytylle childrene, here ye may lere</L>
<L>Moche curtesy &thorn;at is wrytyne here;</L>
<L>For clerkis that the vij arte&yogh; cunne,</L>
<L N="4">Seyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Egerton MS. 1995, synne</NOTE> &thorn;at curtesy from hevyn come</L>
<L>Whan Gabryelle oure lady grette,</L>
<L>And Elizabeth with mary mette.</L>
<L>Alle vertues arne<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben closyde</NOTE> closide yn curtesye,</L>
<L N="8">And alle vices yn vylonye.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;yne hondis be<NOTE PLACE="foot">that thy hondys benne</NOTE> wasshe clene,</L>
<L>That no fylthe on<NOTE PLACE="foot">in</NOTE> thy nayles be sene.</L>
<L>Take &thorn;ou no mete tylle grace<NOTE PLACE="foot">the fyrste gracys</NOTE> be seyde,</L>
<L N="12">And tylle &thorn;ou see alle thyng arayede.</L>
<L>Loke, my son, &thorn;at thow not sytte</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e ruler of &thorn;e hous the bydde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">the halle the bytte</NOTE></L>
<L>And at thy<NOTE PLACE="foot">Atte the</NOTE> mete, yn &thorn;e begynnyng,</L>
<L N="16">Loke on<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-pon (and omits <I>that</I>)</NOTE> pore men that thow thynk,</L>
<L>For the fulle wombe without [<NOTE PLACE="foot">The parts between square brackets [] are from the Egerton MS.</NOTE>any faylys]</L>
<L>Wot fulle lytyl [<NOTE PLACE="foot">The parts between square brackets [] are from the Egerton MS.</NOTE>what the hungery aylys.]</L>
<L>Ete [<NOTE PLACE="foot">The parts between square brackets [] are from the Egerton MS.</NOTE> not thy mete to hastely,</L>
<L N="20">A-byde and ete esely.
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;ou haue thy fulle seruyse,</L>
<L>Touche noo messe in noo wyse.</L>
<L>Kerue not thy brede to thynne,</L>
<L N="24">Ne breke hit not on twynne:</L>
<L>The mosselle that &thorn;ou begynnysse to touche,</L>
<L>Cast them not in thy pouche.</L>
<L>Put not thy fyngerys on thy dysche,</L>
<L N="28">Nothyr in flesche, nothir in fysche.</L>
<L>Put not thy mete in-to the salte,</L>
<L>In-to thy Seler that thy salte halte,]</L>
<L>But ley it fayre<NOTE PLACE="foot">Egerton MS. omits <I>fayre</I></NOTE> on &thorn;i trenchere<MILESTONE N="210b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">The byfore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">To-fore the</NOTE> and &thorn;at is &thorn;yne honore.</L>
<L>Pyke not &thorn;yne Eris ne thy nosterllis;</L>
<L>If<NOTE PLACE="foot">And</NOTE> &thorn;ou do, men wolle sey &thorn;ou come of cherlis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">comyste of karlys</NOTE></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">But</NOTE> whylle &thorn;i mete yn &thorn;i mouth is,</L>
<L N="36">Drynk &thorn;ow not; for-gete not this.</L>
<L>Ete &thorn;i mete by smalle mosselles;</L>
<L>Fylle not thy mouth as done<NOTE PLACE="foot">dothe</NOTE> brothellis.</L>
<L>Pyke not &thorn;i tethe with thy knyfe;</L>
<L N="40">In no company begynne &thorn;ow stryfe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">whyle &thorn;ou ettyste by thy lyffe</NOTE></L>
<L>And whan &thorn;ou hast &thorn;i potage doone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Idone</NOTE></L>
<L>Out of thy dyssh &thorn;ow put thi spone.</L>
<L>Ne spitte &thorn;ow not<NOTE PLACE="foot">spette not</NOTE> over the<NOTE PLACE="foot">thy</NOTE> tabylle,</L>
<L N="44">Ne therupon, for that is no &thorn;ing abylle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nor a-pon hyt, for hyt ys not able</NOTE></L>
<L>Ley not &thorn;yne Elbowe nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">nothyr</NOTE> thy fyst</L>
<L>Vpon the tabylle whylis &thorn;at thow etist.<NOTE PLACE="foot">whyle &thorn;ou este</NOTE></L>
<L>Bulk not as a Beene were yn &thorn;i throte,</L>
<L N="48">[As a ka]rle &thorn;at comys oute of a cote.</L>
<L>[<NOTE PLACE="foot">The parts between square brackets [] are from the Egerton MS.</NOTE>And thy mete be o]f grete pryce,</L>
<L>[Be ware of hyt, or &thorn;ou arte n]ot wyse.</L>
<L>[Speke noo worde stylle ne sterke;
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="20"></L>
<L N="52">And honowre and curtesy loke &thorn;ou kepe,</L>
<L>And at the tabylle loke &thorn;ou make goode chere;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou rownde not in no mannys ere.</L>
<L>With thy fyngerys &thorn;ou towche and taste</L>
<L N="56">Thy mete; And loke &thorn;ou doo noo waste.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou laughe not, nor grenne;</L>
<L>And with moche speche &thorn;ou mayste do synne.</L>
<L>Mete ne drynke loke &thorn;ou ne spylle,</L>
<L N="60">But sette hit downe fayre and stylle.]</L>
<L>Kepe thy cloth clene the byforne,</L>
<L>And bere the so<NOTE PLACE="foot">that</NOTE> thow haue no scorne.<MILESTONE N="207a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Byte not &thorn;i mete, but kerve it<NOTE PLACE="foot">cut hit</NOTE> clene,</L>
<L N="64">Be welle ware no<NOTE PLACE="foot">that noo</NOTE> drop be sene.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou etyst, gape not to wyde</L>
<L>That &thorn;i mouth be sene on yche a<NOTE PLACE="foot">be in euery</NOTE> syde.</L>
<L>And son, beware, I rede, of<NOTE PLACE="foot">be ware of</NOTE> on thyng,</L>
<L N="68">Blow ne&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou not</NOTE> yn thi mete nor yn &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">mete not</NOTE> drynk.</L>
<L>And yif thi lorde drynk at &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Drynk &thorn;ou not, but hym abyde;</L>
<L>Be it at Evyne, be it at noone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">morowe, (and omits next line.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="72">Drynk &thorn;ou not tylle he haue done.</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;i trencher no fyllthe &thorn;ou see,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be sene</NOTE></L>
<L>It is not honest, as I telle the;</L>
<L>Ne drynk<NOTE PLACE="foot">Drynke &thorn;ou not</NOTE> behynde no mannes bakke,</L>
<L N="76">For yf &thorn;ou do, thow art to lakke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">blame</NOTE></L>
<L>And chese come forthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">by-fore the</NOTE> be not to gredy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">redy</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne cutte &thorn;ow not therof to hastely.<NOTE PLACE="foot">To cut there-of be not to gredy.</NOTE></L>
<L>Caste not &thorn;i bones ynto the flore,</L>
<L N="80">But ley &thorn;em<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem</NOTE> fayre on &thorn;i trenchore.</L>
<L>Kepe clene &thorn;i cloth byfore &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e omitted.</NOTE> alle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The parts between square brackets [] are from the Egerton MS.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>And sit &thorn;ou stylle, what so be-falle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">stylle withalle</NOTE></L>
<L>Tylle grace be saide vnto &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L N="84">And tylle &thorn;ou haue wasshen with &thorn;i frende.</L>
<L>Let the more worthy &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">thenne</NOTE> thow</L>
<L>Wassh to-fore<NOTE PLACE="foot">by-fore</NOTE> &thorn;e, &amp; that is &thorn;i prow;</L>
<L>And spitte not yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Spete not on (and omits next line.)</NOTE> &thorn;i basyne,</L>
<L N="88">My swete son, &thorn;at &thorn;ow wasshist yne;</L>
<L>And aryse up soft &amp; stylle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And ryse with hym that sate with the stylle, And thanke hym fayre and welle: Aftyr, Iangely not with Iacke ne gylle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And iangylle nether with Iak ne Iylle,</L>
<L>But take &thorn;i leve of the hede<NOTE PLACE="foot">lorde</NOTE> lowly,<MILESTONE N="207b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="92">And &thorn;ank hym with thyne hert hyghly,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e gentyllis<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e gentylles omitted.</NOTE> togydre yn-same,</L>
<L>And bare the so<NOTE PLACE="foot">soo that</NOTE> thow haue no blame;</L>
<L>Than men wylle<NOTE PLACE="foot">wylle they sey</NOTE> say therafter</L>
<L N="96">That a gentylleman was heere.</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at dispiseth this techyng,</L>
<L>He is not worthy, withoute lesyng,</L>
<L>Nether at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Neuyr at a</NOTE> good mannes tabulle to<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to</NOTE> sitte,</L>
<L N="100">Ner<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nothyr</NOTE> of no worshipe for to wytte.</L>
<L>And therfore, chyldren, for<NOTE PLACE="foot">pur</NOTE> charyte,</L>
<L>Louyth this boke though yt lytil be!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lernythe thys boke that ys callyd Edyllys be</NOTE></L>
<L>And pray for hym &thorn;at made it thus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">made thys</NOTE></L>
<L N="104">That hym may helpe swete Ihesus</L>
<L>To lyve &amp; dye among his frendes,</L>
<L><SUP>16</SUP>And neuer to be combred with no fendes;
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>And geve vs grace yn Ioy to be;</L>
<L N="108">Amen, Amen, for charytee!<SUP>16</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>16-16</SUP> And vs graunte in Ioy to a-byde! Say ye alle Amen for charyde in euery syde.</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT. lerne or be lewde quod Whytyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">AMEN.</NOTE></TRAILER>
<TRAILER>HEre endyth the boke of Curtesy that ys fulle neces|sary vnto yonge chyldryn that muste nedys lerne the maner of curtesy.</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT. AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000167.tif" N="17">
<HEAD>The Young Children's Book.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">
<HEAD>[<I>From the Ashmolean MS.</I> 61 (<I>Bodleian Library</I>), <I>ab.</I> 1500 A.D., <I>fol.</I> 20.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who so euer wylle thryue or the,</L>
<L>Muste vertus lerne, &amp; curtas be;</L>
<L>Fore who in &yogh;owthe no vertus vsythe,</L>
<L N="4">Yn Age All men hym refusythe.</L>
<L>Clerkys &thorn;at canne &thorn;e scyens seuene,</L>
<L>Seys &thorn;at curtasy came fro heuen</L>
<L>When gabryell owre lady grette,</L>
<L N="8">And ely&yogh;abeth with here mette.</L>
<L>All vertus be closyde in curtasy,</L>
<L>And Alle vyces in vilony.</L>
<L>Aryse be tyme oute of thi bedde,</L>
<L N="12">And blysse &thorn;i brest &amp; thi forhede,</L>
<L>Than wasche thi hondes &amp; thi face,</L>
<L>Keme &thorn;i hede, &amp; Aske god grace</L>
<L>The to helpe in All &thorn;i werkes;</L>
<L N="16">Thow schall spede better what so &thorn;ou carpes.</L>
<L>Than go to &thorn;e chyrche, &amp; here A messe,</L>
<L>There aske mersy fore &thorn;i trespasse.</L>
<L>To whom &thorn;ou metys come by &thorn;e weye,</L>
<L N="20">Curtasly 'gode morne' &thorn;ou sey.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou hast done, go breke thy faste</L>
<L>With mete &amp; drynke of gode repaste:</L>
<L>Blysse &thorn;i mouthe or &thorn;ou it ete,</L>
<L N="24">The better schalle be &thorn;i dyete.
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>Be-fore &thorn;i mete sey &thorn;ou &thorn;i grace,</L>
<L>Yt ocupys bot lytell space;&mdash;</L>
<L>Fore oure mete, &amp; drynke, &amp; vs,</L>
<L N="28">Thanke we owre lord Ihesus;&mdash;</L>
<L>A pater noster &amp; Aue mary</L>
<L>Sey fore &thorn;e saulys &thorn;at in peyne ly;</L>
<L>Than go labour as &thorn;ou arte bownde,</L>
<L N="32">And be not Idylle in no stounde:</L>
<L>Holy scryptour &thorn;us it seyth</L>
<L>To &thorn;e &thorn;at Arte of cristen feyth,</L>
<L>"Yffe &thorn;ou labour, &thorn;ou muste ete</L>
<L N="36">That with &thorn;i hondes &thorn;ou doyste gete;"</L>
<L>A byrde hath wenges forto fle,</L>
<L>So man hath Armes laboryd to be.</L>
<L>Luke &thorn;ou be trew in worde &amp; dede,</L>
<L N="40">Yn Alle &thorn;i werkes &thorn;an schall &thorn;ou spede:</L>
<L>Treuth wyt neuer his master schame,</L>
<L>Yt kepys hym out offe synne &amp; blame.</L>
<L>The weys to heuen &thorn;ei bene &thorn;us tweyne,</L>
<L N="44">Mercy &amp; treuthe, As clerkes seyne;</L>
<L>Who so wyll come to &thorn;e lyfe of blysse,</L>
<L>To go &thorn;e weys he may not mysse.</L>
<L>Make no promys bot it be gode,</L>
<L N="48">And kepe &thorn;ou it with myght &amp; mode;</L>
<L>Fore euery promys, it is dette,</L>
<L>That with no falsed muste be lette.</L>
<L>God &amp; &thorn;i neybores lufe all wey;</L>
<L N="52">Welle is &thorn;e, than may &thorn;ou sey,</L>
<L>Fore so &thorn;ou kepys All &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>With-oute Any fere, drede, or awe.</L>
<L>Vn-callyd go &thorn;ou to no counselle;</L>
<L N="56">That longes to &thorn;e, with &thorn;at thow melle.</L>
<L>Scorne not &thorn;e pore, ne hurte no mane;</L>
<L>Lerne of hym &thorn;at the teche cane;</L>
<L>Be no glosere nor no mokere,</L>
<L N="60">Ne no seruantes no wey lokere.
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>Be not prowd, bot meke &amp; lynd,</L>
<L>And with thi better go &thorn;ou be-hynd.</L>
<L>When &thorn;i better schewys his wylle,</L>
<L N="64">To he haue seyd &thorn;ou muste be stylle.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou spekes to Any mane,</L>
<L>Hande, fote, &amp; fynger, kepe &thorn;ou styll &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And luke &thorn;ou vppe in to his face,</L>
<L N="68">And curtase be in euery place.</L>
<L>With &thorn;i fynger schew &thorn;ou no thynge,</L>
<L>Nor be not lefe to telle tydinge.</L>
<L>Yff Any man sey welle of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="72">Or of thi frendes, thankyd muste be.</L>
<L>Haue few wordes, &amp; wysly sette,</L>
<L>Fore so &thorn;ou may thi worschyppe gete.</L>
<L>Vse no suerynge no&thorn;er lyenge,</L>
<L N="76">Yn thi sellynge &amp; thi byenge,</L>
<L>Fore &amp; &thorn;ou do &thorn;ou arte to blame,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last &thorn;ou wylle haue schame.</L>
<L>Gete &thorn;i gowd with trewe[t]h &amp; wynne,</L>
<L N="80">And kepe &thorn;e out of dette &amp; synne.</L>
<L>Be loth to greue, &amp; leffe to ples;</L>
<L>Seke &thorn;e pes, &amp; lyfe in es.</L>
<L>Offe whome &thorn;ou spekes, where &amp; when,</L>
<L N="84">A-vyse &thorn;e welle, &amp; to what men.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou commys vn to A dore,</L>
<L>Sey "god be here," or &thorn;ou go ferre:</L>
<L>Wer-euer &thorn;ou commys, speke honestly</L>
<L N="88">To ser or dame, or &thorn;er meny.</L>
<L>Stand, &amp; sytte not furth-with-alle</L>
<L>Tylle he byde &thorn;e &thorn;at rewlys &thorn;e halle;</L>
<L>Where he bydis, &thorn;er must &thorn;ou sytte,</L>
<L N="92">And fore none o&thorn;er change ne flyte;</L>
<L>Sytt vp-ryght And honestly,</L>
<L>Ete &amp; drinke, &amp; be feleyly,</L>
<L>Parte with hem &thorn;at sytes &thorn;e by,</L>
<L N="96">Thus teches &thorn;e dame curtasy.
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>Take &thorn;e salt with thi clene knyfe;</L>
<L>Be cold of spech, &amp; make no stryfe;</L>
<L>Bakbyte no man &thorn;at is A-weye,</L>
<L N="100">Be glad of Alle men wele to sey.</L>
<L>Here &amp; se, &amp; sey thou nought,</L>
<L>Than schall &thorn;ou not to profe be brought.</L>
<L>With mete &amp; drynke be-fore &thorn;e sette,</L>
<L N="104">Hold &thorn;e plesyd, &amp; aske no bette.</L>
<L>Wype thi mouthe when &thorn;ou wyll drinke,</L>
<L>Lest it foule thi copys brinke;</L>
<L>Kepe clene thi fyngeres, lypes, &amp; chine,</L>
<L N="108">Fore &thorn;ou may thi wyrschype wynne.</L>
<L>Yn &thorn;i mouth when &thorn;i mete is,</L>
<L>To drinke, or speke, or lau&yogh;h, I-wys</L>
<L>Dame curtasy fore-bydes it the:</L>
<L N="112">Bot prayse thi fare, wer-so-euer &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>Fore be it gode or be it badde,</L>
<L>Yn gud worth it muste be had.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou spytes, be welle were</L>
<L N="116">Where to &thorn;ou spytes, ny&yogh;e or fere;</L>
<L>Hold &thorn;i hand be-fore thi mouth</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou spytes, &amp; hyde it couth.</L>
<L>Kepe &thorn;i knyfe both clene &amp; scherpe,</L>
<L N="120">And be not besy forto kerpe;</L>
<L>Clens &thorn;i knyfe with some cutte bred,</L>
<L>Not with thi cloth, As I &thorn;e rede:</L>
<L>With Any fylth to fowle &thorn;e clothe,</L>
<L N="124">A curtase mane he wylle be lothe.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i dysch sette not &thorn;i spone,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er on &thorn;e brynke, os vn-lernyd done.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou sopys, make no no[y]se</L>
<L N="128">With thi mouth As do boys.</L>
<L>The mete &thorn;at on &thorn;i trencher is,</L>
<L>Putte it not in-to &thorn;i dysch.</L>
<L>Gete &thorn;e sone A-voyde,</L>
<L N="132">And sone A-voyd &thorn;ou thi trenchere.
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>When thi better take &thorn;e tho coppe,</L>
<L>Drinke thi selffe, &amp; sette it vppe,</L>
<L>Take tho coppe with thi hondes</L>
<L N="136">Lest it falle &thorn;er As &thorn;ou stondes.</L>
<L>When thi better spekes to the,</L>
<L>Do offe thi cape &amp; bow &thorn;i kne.</L>
<L>At thi tabull no&thorn;er crache ne claw,</L>
<L N="140">Than men wylle sey &thorn;ou arte A daw.</L>
<L>Wype not thi nose nor &thorn;i nos-thirlys,</L>
<L>Than mene wylle sey &thorn;ou come of cherlys.</L>
<L>Make &thorn;ou no&thorn;er cate ne hond</L>
<L N="144">Thi felow at &thorn;ou tabull round;</L>
<L>Ne pleye with spone, trenchere, ne knyffe.</L>
<L>Yn honesty &amp; clenys lede &thorn;ou thi lyffe.</L>
<L>This boke is made for chylde &yogh;onge</L>
<L N="148">At the scowle &thorn;at byde not longe:</L>
<L>Sone it may be conyd &amp; had,</L>
<L>And make them gode iff &thorn;ei be bad.</L>
<L>God gyffe them grace, vertuos to be,</L>
<L N="152">Fore than &thorn;ei may both thryff &amp; the.</L>
<TRAILER>Amen! quod Kate.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<DIV2 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="26">
<HEAD>Stans Puer ad Mensam. ASCRIBED TO JOHN LIDGATE.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[MS. Harl. 2251,? about 1460 A.D., fol. 153 or 148. The parts between brackets [ ], and various readings, are from Mr Halliwell's print in <I>Reliqui&aelig; Antiqu&aelig;</I>, v. 1, p. 156-8, of a 15th|century MS. Q. T. 8, fol. 77, r<SUP>o</SUP>, in the Library of Jesus College, Cambridge.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; [My dere childe, first thiself enable</L>
<L>With all thin herte to vertuous disciplyne</L>
<L>Afor thi soverayne standing at the table,</L>
<L N="4">Dispose thi youth aftir my doctryne</L>
<L>To all norture thi corage to enclyne.</L>
<L>First when thu spekist be not rekles,</L>
<L>Kepe feete and fingeris and handes still in pese.]</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BE symple of chiere, cast nat thyn ye aside,</L>
<L>Agenst the post lete nat thy bak abyde;</L>
<L>Gaase nat aboute, tournyng ouer alle;</L>
<L>Make nat thi myrrour also of the walle,</L>
<L N="12">Pyke nat thy nose, and in especialle</L>
<L>Be right wele ware, and sette hieron thi thought,</L>
<L>By-fore thy souerayne cracche ne rubbe nought.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who spekithe to the in any maner place,</L>
<L N="16">Rudely<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rel. Ant.</I>, Lumbisshly</NOTE> cast nat thyn ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">hede</NOTE> adowne,</L>
<L>But with a sadde chiere loke hym in the face;</L>
<L>Walke demurely by strete in the towne,</L>
<L>Advertise the withe wisdom and Reasoune.</L>
<L N="20">Withe dissolute laughters do thow non offence</L>
<L>To-fore thy souerayn, whiles he is in presence.
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Pare clene thy nailes, thyn handes wasshe also</L>
<L>To-fore mete, and whan thow dooest arise;</L>
<L N="24">Sitte in that place thow art assigned to;</L>
<L>Prease nat to hye in no maner wise;</L>
<L>And til thow se afore the thy service,</L>
<L>Be nat to hasty on brede for to byte,</L>
<L N="28">Of gredynesse lest men wolde the endwyte.<NOTE PLACE="foot">a-wite.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Grennyng and mowes at the table eschowe;</L>
<L>Cry nat to loude; kepe honestly silence;</L>
<L>To enboce thy Iowis withe mete<NOTE PLACE="foot">brede it</NOTE> is nat diewe;</L>
<L N="32">With ful mowthe speke nat, lest thow do offence;</L>
<L>Drynk nat bretheles<NOTE PLACE="foot">bridlid</NOTE> for hast ne necligence;</L>
<L>Kepe clene thy lippes from fat of flesshe or fysshe;</L>
<L>Wype clene<NOTE PLACE="foot">fayre</NOTE> thi spone, leve it nat in thy disshe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="36">&para; Of brede I-byten no soppis that thow make;</L>
<L>In ale nor wyne withe hande leve no fattenes;</L>
<L>With mowthe enbrewed thi cuppe thou nat take;</L>
<L>Enbrewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Foul</NOTE> no napery for no rekelesnes;</L>
<L N="40">For to souppe [loude] is agenst gentiles;</L>
<L>[N]evyr at mete begynne thow nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">be warre gynne no</NOTE> stryfe;</L>
<L>Thi teth also thow pike nat with no knyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of honest myrth latt be thy daliaunce;<MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="44">Swere none othes, speke no ribawdrye;</L>
<L>The best morsel, have in remembraunce,</L>
<L>Hole to thyself alway do nat applie;</L>
<L>Part with thy felaw, for that is curtesie:</L>
<L N="48">Laade not thy trenchour with many remyssailes;</L>
<L>And frome blaknes alwey kepe thy nayles.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of curtesye also agenst the lawe,</L>
<L>With sowne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Which sou</NOTE> dishonest for to do offence;</L>
<L N="52">Of old surfaytes abrayde nat thy felawe;</L>
<L>Toward thy souerayne alwey thyn aduertence;
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>Play withe no knyf, take heede to my sentence;</L>
<L>At mete and soupper kepe the stille and soft;</L>
<L N="56">Eke to and fro meve nat thy foote to oft.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Droppe nat thi brest withe sawce ne with potage;</L>
<L>Brynge no knyves vnskoured to the table;</L>
<L>Fil nat thy spone, lest in the cariage</L>
<L N="60">It went beside, whiche were nat comendable;</L>
<L>Be quyke and redy, meke and seruisable,</L>
<L>Wele awaityng to fulfylle anone</L>
<L>What that thy souerayne comav[n]dithe the to be done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">&para; And whare-so euer that thow dyne or soupe,</L>
<L>Of gentilesse take salt withe thy knyf;</L>
<L>And be wele ware thow blowe nat in the cuppe.</L>
<L>Reuerence thy felawe, gynne withe hym no stryf;</L>
<L N="68">Be thy powere kepe pees all thy lyf.</L>
<L>Interrupt nat, where so thow wende,</L>
<L>None other mans tale, til he have made an ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; With thy fyngres make<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rel. Ant.</I>, marke</NOTE> thow nat thy tale;</L>
<L N="72">Be wele avised, namly in tendre age,</L>
<L>To drynk by mesure bothe wyne and ale;</L>
<L>Be nat copious also of langage;</L>
<L>As tyme requyrithe, shewe out thy visage,</L>
<L N="76">To gladde ne to sory, but kepe atwene tweyne,</L>
<L>For losse or lucre or any case sodayne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Be meke in mesure, nat hasti, but tretable;<MILESTONE N="154a" UNIT="folio"><MILESTONE N="149a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ouer moche is nat worthe in no maner thyng;</L>
<L N="80">To children it longithe nat to be [vengeable,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Harl., tretable</NOTE>]</L>
<L>Sone meved and sone forgyvyng;</L>
<L>And as it is remembrid bi<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rel. Ant.</I>, by olde</NOTE> writyng,</L>
<L>Wrathe of children is sone ouergone,</L>
<L N="84">With an apple the parties be made at one.
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In children werre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Rel. Ant.</I>, In childre</NOTE> now myrthe and now debate,</L>
<L>In theyr quarel no grete violence;</L>
<L>Now pley, now wepyng, sielde in one estate;</L>
<L N="88">To theyr playntes gyve no credence;</L>
<L>A Rodde refourmythe all theyr insolence;</L>
<L>In theyr corage no Rancour dothe abyde;</L>
<L>Who sparithe the yerd, all vertue set aside.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>LENVOYE.</HEAD>
<L N="92">Go, litel bille, bareyn of eloquence,</L>
<L>Pray yonge children that the shal see or Reede,</L>
<L>Thoughe thow be compendious of sentence,</L>
<L>Of thi clauses for to taken heede,</L>
<L N="96">Whiche to al vertu shal theyr yowthe leede.</L>
<L>Of the writyng, thoughe ther be no date,</L>
<L>If ought be mysse,&mdash;worde, sillable, or dede,&mdash;</L>
<L>Put all the defaute vpon John Lydegate.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="27">
<HEAD>The Book of Curteisie That is Clepid Stans Puer ad Mensam.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 150, <I>back. Part written as prose.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mi dere sone, first &thorn;i silf able</L>
<L>with al &thorn;in herte to vertuose discipline,&mdash;</L>
<L>A-fore &thorn;i souereyn stondinge at &thorn;e table</L>
<L N="4">Dispose &thorn;ou &thorn;ee aftir my doctryne&mdash;</L>
<L>To al nortur &thorn;i corage to encline.</L>
<L>First while &thorn;ou spekist, be not richelees;</L>
<L>Kepe bo&thorn;e fyngir and hond stille in pees.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="8">Be symple in cheer; caste not &thorn;i looke a-side,<MILESTONE N="151" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>gase not about, turnynge &thorn;i si&yogh;t oueral.</L>
<L>a&yogh;en &thorn;e post lete not &thorn;i bak abide,</L>
<L>nei&thorn;er make &thorn;i myrrour also of &thorn;e wal.</L>
<L N="12">Pike not &thorn;i nose; &amp; moost in especial</L>
<L>be weel waar, sette her-on &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>to-fore &thorn;i souereyn cratche ne picke &thorn;ee nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who-so speke to &thorn;ee in ony maner place,</L>
<L N="16">lumpischli caste not &thorn;in heed a-doun,</L>
<L>but with a sad cheer loke him in &thorn;e face.</L>
<L>walke demurely bi streetis in &thorn;e toun,</L>
<L>And take good hede bi wisdom &amp; resoun</L>
<L N="20">&thorn;at bi no wantowne lau&yogh;inge &thorn;ou do noon offence</L>
<L>To-fore &thorn;i souereyne while he is in presence.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pare clene &thorn;i nailis; &thorn;in hondis waische also</L>
<L>to-fore &thorn;i mete, [&amp;] whanne &thorn;ou doist arise.</L>
<L N="24">sitte &thorn;ou in &thorn;at place &thorn;at &thorn;ou art a-signed to;</L>
<L>Prece not to hie in no maner wise;</L>
<L>And whanne &thorn;ou seest afore &thorn;ee &thorn;i seruice,</L>
<L>be not to hasti upon breed to bite</L>
<L N="28">lest men &thorn;erof Do &thorn;ee edwite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Grennynge &amp; mowynge at &thorn;i table eschewe;<MILESTONE N="152" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Crie not to lowde: honestli kepe silence.</L>
<L>To enbrace &thorn;i iowis with breed, it is not dewe;</L>
<L N="32">with ful mou&thorn; speke not lest &thorn;ou do offence;</L>
<L>Drinke not bridelid for haste ne necligence;</L>
<L>Kepe clene &thorn;i lippis from fleisch &amp; fische;</L>
<L>Wipe faire &thorn;i spoon; leue it not in &thorn;i dische.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="36">Of breed with &thorn;i tee&thorn; no soppis &thorn;ou make;</L>
<L>Lowde for to soupe is a&yogh;en gentilnes:</L>
<L>With mou&thorn; enbrowide &thorn;i cuppe &thorn;ou not take,</L>
<L>In ale ne in wiyn with hond leue no fatnes;</L>
<L N="40">Defoule not &thorn;e naprie bi no richelesnes.</L>
<L>Be waar &thorn;at at &thorn;e mete &thorn;ou bigynne no striif;</L>
<L>&THORN;i tee&thorn; also at &thorn;e table picke with no knyf.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of honest mir&thorn;e euere be &thorn;i daliaunce;</L>
<L N="44">Swere noon oo&thorn;is; speke no ribaudie.</L>
<L>&THORN;e beste morsels,&mdash;haue &thorn;is in remembraunce,&mdash;</L>
<L>Holli alwey &thorn;i silf to take do not applie.</L>
<L>Parte with &thorn;i felawis, for &thorn;at is curteisie.</L>
<L N="48">Lete not &thorn;i trenchour be with many morsels;</L>
<L>And fro blaknes kepe weel &thorn;i nailis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of curtesie it is a&yogh;en &thorn;e lawe,<MILESTONE N="153" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>With dishoneste, sone, for to do difence;</L>
<L N="52">Of oolde forfetis vpbraide not &thorn;i felawe;</L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;i souereyn do euere reuerence.
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>Pleie with no knif, take hede to my sentence;</L>
<L>At mete &amp; at soper kepe &thorn;ee stille &amp; softe,</L>
<L N="56">And eek to &amp; fro meeue not &thorn;i fee&thorn; to ofte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Droppe not &thorn;i brest with seew &amp; o&thorn;er potage,</L>
<L>Bringe no foule knyues vnto &thorn;e table;</L>
<L>Fille not &thorn;i spoon lest in &thorn;e cariage</L>
<L N="60">It scheede bi side, it were not commendable.</L>
<L>Be quik &amp; redi, meke &amp; seruiable,</L>
<L>Weel awaitinge to fulfille anoon</L>
<L>What &thorn;at &thorn;i souereyn commaundi&thorn; to be doon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="64">And where-so-euere &thorn;ou be to digne or to suppe,</L>
<L>Of gentilnes take salt with &thorn;i knyf,</L>
<L>And be weel waar &thorn;ou blowe not in &thorn;e cuppe.</L>
<L>Reuerence &thorn;i felawis; bigynne with hem no strijf;</L>
<L N="68">To &thorn;i power kepe pees al &thorn;i lijf.</L>
<L>Intrippe no man where so &thorn;at &thorn;ou wende,</L>
<L>No man in his tale, til he haue maade an eende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; With &thorn;i fyngris marke not &thorn;i tale;<MILESTONE N="154" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="72">be weel avysid, &amp; nameli in tendir age,</L>
<L>To drinke mesurabli bo&thorn;e wiyn &amp; ale.</L>
<L>Be not to copiose of langage;</L>
<L>As tyme requiri&thorn; schewe out &thorn;i visage,</L>
<L N="76">To glad, ne to sory, but kepe &thorn;ee euene bitwene</L>
<L>For los, or lucre, or ony case sodene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be soft in mesure, not hasti, but treteable;</L>
<L>Ouer soft is nou&yogh;t in no maner &thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="80">To children longi&thorn; not to be vengeable,</L>
<L>Soone meued and soone fi&yogh;tinge;</L>
<L>And as it is remembrid bi writynge,</L>
<L>wra&thorn;&thorn;e of children is ouercome soone,</L>
<L N="84">With &thorn;e partis of an appil ben made at oon.
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In children werre is now mir&thorn;e &amp; now debate,</L>
<L>In her quarel is no violence,</L>
<L>now pleie, now wepinge, &amp; seelde in oon state;</L>
<L N="88">to her pleyntis &yogh;eue no credence;</L>
<L>A rodde reforme&thorn; al her necligence;</L>
<L>in her corage no rancour doo&thorn; abide,</L>
<L>who &thorn;at spari&thorn; &thorn;e rodde all uertues setti&thorn; a-side.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="92"><B>A</B>! litil balade, voide of eloquence,<MILESTONE N="155" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I praie &yogh;ou &yogh;onge children &thorn;at &thorn;is schal se &amp; rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &yogh;e be copious of sentence,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it to &thorn;ese clausis for to take hede</L>
<L N="96">Which al into vertues schal &yogh;oure &yogh;ou&thorn;e lede.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is writynge, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;er be no date,</L>
<L>Yf ou&yogh;t be mys in word, sillable, or dede,</L>
<L>I submitte me to correccioun withoute ony debate.</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Thus eendith &thorn;e book of curteisie &thorn;at is clepid stans puer ad mensam.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="34">
<HEAD>Of the Manners to bring one to Honour and Welfare.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SOne, y schal &thorn;ee schewe,&mdash;now take hede,&mdash;</L>
<L>And of suche maners &thorn;ee declare</L>
<L>Bi whiche &thorn;ou schalt come to manhede,</L>
<L N="4">To wordli worschip, and to weelfare.</L>
<L>&para; What man &thorn;ou seruest, euermore him drede,</L>
<L>And hise goodis as &thorn;in owne euere &thorn;ou spare;</L>
<L>Lete neuere &thorn;i wil &thorn;i witt ouer lede;</L>
<L N="8">Of wra&thorn;ful wordis euermore be ware.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e bigynnynge of &thorn;i worschip, is to drede schame;</L>
<L>Lete o&thorn;ere men talke her talis or &thorn;ou,</L>
<L>And her wittis loke &thorn;ou not blame;<MILESTONE N="166" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="12">Vnto &thorn;i betere euermore &thorn;ou bowe;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And whanne &thorn;ou schalt boorde, bourde with &thorn;i peere,</L>
<L>And leue of to pleie whanne &thorn;ee list best.</L>
<L>And for to suffre greete wordis, is manere,</L>
<L N="16">And often tyme it is betere to bow &thorn;an to berst;</L>
<L>And of euery mannis witt loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou lere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at rial tresour &thorn;ou close in &thorn;i chest;</L>
<L>Telle neuere &thorn;e more &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou myche heere,</L>
<L N="20">And euere be waare of had-y-wist.</L>
<L>In companies be neuere to tale-wijs,</L>
<L>Ne ouer myrie, ne ouer sadde,</L>
<L>Lest in &thorn;i berynge men acounte &thorn;ee ouer nyce;</L>
<L N="24">Kepe euere &thorn;e meene, and euere be a-drad.
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="35"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; With bro&thorn;els ne boies loke &thorn;ou with hem neuere play,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;ou hem tellist &thorn;ou schalt heere eft.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou se a wastour owher, y &thorn;ee pray,</L>
<L N="28">His felowschip fayn y wolde &thorn;at &thorn;ou left.</L>
<L>&para; Medle not with mysrule by no maner way,</L>
<L>For good maner he ha&thorn; from hym schifte;</L>
<L>For y haue ofte seen &thorn;is in fay,<MILESTONE N="157" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at fro manye men he ha&thorn; manhode refte.<NOTE PLACE="end">[? one stanza of 4 lines wanting]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Take what you find or what you bring.<NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>MS. Trin. Coll. Cambridge</I>, O. 9.38.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>hoo that comy&yogh;t to an howse,</L>
<L>loke he be noo thyng' dongerowse</L>
<L>To take seche as he fyndy&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="4">And yf he wolle not do soo,</L>
<L>Reson A-gree&yogh;t there-too</L>
<L>To take suche as he bryngy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Reward of the Man who Beggars Himself.<NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>MS. Trin. Coll. Cambridge</I>, O. 9.38, <I>written as prose.</I>]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>with thys bytel be he smete. &thorn;at alle &thorn;e worle mote hyt wete</L>
<L>&THORN;at yevyt hys goode to hys kynne. &amp; goth hym sylfe A beggyng'
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000186.tif" N="36">
<HEAD>How the Good Wiff tau&yogh;te Hir Dou&yogh;tir.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Lambeth MS. 853, ab. 1430 A.D., page 102; written without breaks. The various readings are from one of the MS. volumes of Lydgate's Works in Trin. Coll. Camb. Library, R. 3.19. I owe the readings to the kindness of Mr W. Aldis Wright.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The good wijf tau&yogh;te hir dou&yogh;tir</L>
<L>Ful<SUP>1</SUP> manye a tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">Many tymes</NOTE> &amp; ofte</L>
<L>A ful<SUP>1</SUP> good womman to be,</L>
<L N="4">And seide "dou&yogh;tir to<SUP>1</SUP> me<SUP>1</SUP> dere,</L>
<L>Sum good &thorn;ou must lere</L>
<L>If euere<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>1-1</SUP> Omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;ee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dou&yogh;tir, if &thorn;ou wolt ben a wijf,<SUP>3</SUP></L>
<L N="8">Loke wijsly &thorn;at &thorn;ou worche,</L>
<L>Loke loueli <MILESTONE N="103" UNIT="page">and in good lijf</L>
<L>&THORN;ou loue god &amp; holi chirche.<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>3-3</SUP> wyse &amp; wysely wyrke Loke thow loue welle thy god and holy chyrche</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Go to chirche whanne &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L N="12">Loke &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp;</NOTE> spare for no reyn,</L>
<L><SUP>5</SUP>For &thorn;ou farist &thorn;e best &thorn;at ilke day</L>
<L>Whanne<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>5-5</SUP> Alle the day thow faryst the bet &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;ou hast god y-seyn.</L>
<L>&para; <SUP>6</SUP>He muste need weel &thorn;riue</L>
<L N="16">&thorn;at liue&thorn; weel al his lyue,<SUP>6</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>6-6</SUP> Welle proueth that god loueth</NOTE></L>
<L>My leef child.
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gladli<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gladly thow</NOTE> &yogh;eue &thorn;i ti&thorn;is &amp; &thorn;in offrynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">offrynges</NOTE> bo&thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;e poore &amp; &thorn;e beedered, loke &thorn;ou not<NOTE PLACE="foot">bedered &thorn;at &thorn;ey be thee nat</NOTE> lo&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="20">&YOGH;eue of &thorn;in owne good, and be<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eue thow hem of thy good and be &thorn;ou</NOTE> not to hard,</L>
<L>For seelden is &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">seldom ys the</NOTE> hous poore &thorn;ere god is steward.</L>
<L><SUP>6</SUP>Weel he proue&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e poore loue&thorn;,<SUP>6</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>6-6</SUP> Welle he tresoreth that the poore honowreth</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne<NOTE PLACE="foot">And when</NOTE> &thorn;ou sittist in &thorn;e chirche, &thorn;i beedis &thorn;ou schalt<NOTE PLACE="foot">bedys to</NOTE> bidde;</L>
<L><SUP>9</SUP>Make &thorn;ou no iangelynge To freende nor to sibbe;<SUP>9</SUP></L>
<L>lau&yogh;e &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">lawe &thorn;ou nat</NOTE> to scorne nou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">neyther</NOTE> oolde bodi<SUP>9</SUP> ne &yogh;onge,</L>
<L N="28">But be of fair beerynge &amp; of good tunge;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; &thorn;i fair beerynge</L>
<L>&THORN;i worschip ha&thorn; encresynge,</L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="32">&para; If ony man biddi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Yef any man bid</NOTE> &thorn;e worschip, and wolde wedde &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou scorne him not,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat. (Throughout, <I>nat</I> is written for <I>not.</I>)</NOTE> what-so-euere he be,</L>
<L>But<SUP>9</SUP> schewe it to &thorn;i freendis, &amp; for-hile &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">forhele</NOTE> it nou&yogh;t;<MILESTONE N="104" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Sitte not<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat. (Throughout, <I>nat</I> is written for <I>not.</I>)</NOTE> bi him, nei&thorn;er stoonde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">stand</NOTE> &thorn;ere synne my&yogh;te be wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="36">For<SUP>9</SUP> a sclaundre reisid ille<SUP>9</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>9-9</SUP> Omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Is yuel for to stille,</L>
<L>Mi leue childe.
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>That man &thorn;at schal &thorn;e wedde bifor god wi&thorn; a ryng,</L>
<L N="40">Loue &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> him &amp; honoure moost of er&thorn;eli &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Meekely &thorn;ou him answere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Answere hym faire</NOTE> And not<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat</NOTE> as an attir|ling,</L>
<L>And so maist &thorn;ou slake<NOTE PLACE="foot">thow shalt stylle</NOTE> his mood, And ben his dere derlynge:</L>
<L>A fair worde <SUP>5</SUP>and a meeke</L>
<L N="44">doo&thorn; wra&thorn;&thorn;e slake,<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>5-5</SUP> to &thorn;y make oft wrethe doth stake</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fair of speche schalt &thorn;ou be, gladde, &amp; of mylde mood,</L>
<L>Trewe in worde &amp; in dede, and in conscience<NOTE PLACE="foot">thy conscyence</NOTE> good;</L>
<L N="48">Kepe &thorn;ee from synne, fro vilonye, &amp; fro blame,</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;ou beere &thorn;ee so &thorn;at men seie &thorn;ee no schame;</L>
<L><SUP>7</SUP>For he &thorn;at in good lijf renne&thorn;,</L>
<L>Ful ofte weel he wynne&thorn;,<SUP>7</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>7-7</SUP> Good lyfe reneweth and welle wynneth</NOTE></L>
<L N="52">Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><SUP>8</SUP>Be of semeli semblaunt, wijs, and o&thorn;er<SUP>8</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>8-8</SUP> Of fayre semblant shalt thow be, wys, and of good manere</NOTE> good maner,</L>
<L>Chaunge not &thorn;i contynaunce for nou&yogh;t &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="105" UNIT="page"> &thorn;ou may heere;</L>
<L>Fare not<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat</NOTE> as a gigge, for nou&yogh;t &thorn;at may bitide,</L>
<L N="56">Lau&yogh;e &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> not to loude,<SUP>9</SUP> ne &yogh;ane &thorn;ou not to<SUP>9</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>9-9</SUP> long, ne yane nat</NOTE> wide,</L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>But lau&yogh;e &thorn;ou softe &amp; myelde,</L>
<L>And be not of cheer to wielde,<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10-10</SUP> Yet lawgh thow may &amp; mery wordys say</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="60">And whan &thorn;ou goist in &thorn;e way, go &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> not to faste,</L>
<L>Braundische not with &thorn;in heed, &thorn;i schuldris &thorn;ou ne caste;</L>
<L>Haue &thorn;ou not to manye wordis; to swere be &thorn;ou not leefe,</L>
<L>For alle such maners comen to an yuel preef:</L>
<L N="64"><SUP>2</SUP>For he &thorn;at cacchi&thorn; to him an yuel name,</L>
<L>It is to him a foule fame,<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>2-2</SUP> Euylle name ys euelle fame</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue childe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Go &thorn;ou not into &thorn;e toun as it were a gase</L>
<L N="68">From oon hous to ano&thorn;er for to seke &thorn;e mase;</L>
<L>Ne wende &thorn;ou not to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> market &thorn;i borel<NOTE PLACE="foot">borelle</NOTE> for to selle,</L>
<L>And &THORN;anne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne</NOTE> to &thorn;e tauerne &thorn;i worschip to felle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for to fylle</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>6</SUP>For &thorn;ei &thorn;at tauernes haunten,</L>
<L N="72">Her &THORN;rifte &thorn;ei adaunten,<SUP>6</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>6-6</SUP> He that tauernes haunteth, hyr thryft adaunteth</NOTE></L>
<L>My leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if &thorn;ou be in place where<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere</NOTE> good ale is on lofte,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ou serue <MILESTONE N="106" UNIT="page">&thorn;erof, or &thorn;at &thorn;ou sitte softe,</L>
<L N="76">Mesurabli<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mesurely</NOTE> &thorn;ou take &thorn;er-of &thorn;at &thorn;ou falle in no blame,</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ou be ofte drunke, it falle<NOTE PLACE="foot">hit falleth</NOTE> &thorn;ee to schame;</L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>For &thorn;o &thorn;at ben ofte drunke,</L>
<L>&THORN;rift is from hem sunke,<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10-10</SUP> He &thorn;at ys oft drunke, thryft ys fro hym sonke,</NOTE></L>
<L N="80">Mi leue child.
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Go not to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> wrastelinge, ne to schotynge at<NOTE PLACE="foot">shetyng at &thorn;e</NOTE> cok,</L>
<L>As it were a strumpet or a gigggelot:</L>
<L>wone<NOTE PLACE="foot">Syt</NOTE> at hom, dou&yogh;tir, and loue &thorn;i werk myche,</L>
<L N="84">And so &thorn;ou schalt, my leue child, wexe soone riche.</L>
<L><SUP>4</SUP>It is euermore a myrie &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>A man to be serued of his owne &thorn;ing,<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>4-4</SUP> Mery[er] ys owne thyng on to loke &thorn;an any o&thorn;er mannys on to tote</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="88">Aqweynte &thorn;ee not with eche man &thorn;at goo&thorn; bi &thorn;e strete;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; ony man speke<NOTE PLACE="foot">he speke feyre</NOTE> to &thorn;ee, Swiftli &thorn;ou him grete;</L>
<L>Lete him go bi &thorn;e wey; bi him &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">nat</NOTE> stonde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> bi no vilonye &thorn;in herte my&yogh;te fonde,</L>
<L N="92"><SUP>7</SUP>For alle men ben not trewe</L>
<L>&THORN;at kunne fair her wordis schewe,<SUP>7</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>7-7</SUP>For alle men be nat trew &thorn;at feyre spekyn</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne</NOTE> for no coueitise, &yogh;iftis &thorn;at &thorn;ou <MILESTONE N="107" UNIT="page">noon take;</L>
<L N="96">But &thorn;ou wite ri&yogh;t weel whi ellis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> soone &thorn;ou hem forsake,</L>
<L>For with &yogh;iftis men may wommen<NOTE PLACE="foot">wemen</NOTE> ouer goon</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei were as trewe as steel ei&thorn;er stoon.</L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>Bounden forso&thorn;e sche is</L>
<L N="100">&thorn;at of ony man taki&thorn; &yogh;iftis,<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10-10</SUP> For boundyn ys she &thorn;at taketh yeftys</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue childe.
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="41"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wijsli gouerne &thorn;ou &thorn;in hous and &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">Gouerne welle also thyne howse &amp; wysely thy</NOTE> meyne:</L>
<L>To bittir ne to bonour with hem &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne<SUP>2</SUP> be,</L>
<L N="104">But<SUP>2</SUP> loke weel<NOTE PLACE="foot">welle abowte</NOTE> what is moost neede to doone,</L>
<L>And sette &thorn;i meyne &thorn;erto bo&thorn;e ratheli<NOTE PLACE="foot">and &thorn;at lyghtly</NOTE> &amp; soone,</L>
<L>For redi is at nede</L>
<L>A forn doon dede,</L>
<L N="108">Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if &thorn;in husbonde be from<NOTE PLACE="foot">yef &thorn;y mastyr be fro</NOTE> hoome, lete not</L>
<L>&thorn;i meyne goon<NOTE PLACE="foot">go</NOTE> ydil,</L>
<L>But loke weel who doo&thorn; myche<NOTE PLACE="foot">mykylle</NOTE> ei&thorn;er litil,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at weel doo&thorn;, &THORN;ou<SUP>2</SUP> qwite him weel his whyle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Trin. Coll. MS. whyle. (<I>The Lambeth MS. has</I> mede.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">And he &thorn;at doo&thorn; o&thorn;er, serue him as &thorn;e vile</L>
<L>A forn doon dede</L>
<L>Wole ano&thorn;er spede,</L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="116">And if &thorn;i nede be greet &amp; &thorn;i tyme streite,</L>
<L>&THORN;an<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>2-2</SUP> Omitted.</NOTE> go &thorn;i silf &thorn;erto &amp; worche <MILESTONE N="108" UNIT="page">an houswijfes<NOTE PLACE="foot">and make a wyues breyde</NOTE> brayde,</L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>&THORN;anne wille &thorn;ei alle do &thorn;e bettir &thorn;at aboute &thorn;ee stande[s].<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10-10</SUP> Alle &thorn;ey doon the bettyr &thorn;at about &thorn;ee stondyn</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e work is &thorn;e sonner do &thorn;at ha&thorn; many handis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hondyn</NOTE></L>
<L N="120"><SUP>12</SUP>For manye handis &amp; wight</L>
<L>Make an heuy worke light;</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;i good seruise</L>
<L>&THORN;i name schal arise,<SUP>12</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>12-12</SUP> Many hondys &amp; smert makyn lyght werke</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">Mi leue childe.
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">Loke</NOTE> what so<SUP>2</SUP> &thorn;i meyne do, aboute<NOTE PLACE="foot">and about</NOTE> hem &thorn;ou wende,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">At euery dede &thorn;at shuld be do</NOTE> as myche as &thorn;ou maist, be at &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">the</NOTE> oon eende,</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou fynde ony<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyndyst a</NOTE> defaute, do it soone<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone do hit</NOTE> ameende</L>
<L N="128">So<NOTE PLACE="foot">So &thorn;at</NOTE> &thorn;ei haue tyme<SUP>2</SUP> and<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>2-2</SUP> Omitted.</NOTE> space &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &thorn;ey</NOTE> may hem de|fende.</L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>To compelle a dede to be doon &amp; &thorn;ere be no space,</L>
<L>It is but tyrannye with-out temper|aunce &amp; grace,<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10-10</SUP> Meche besynesse behoueth hem &thorn;at shall howse holden</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="132"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>The next two stanzas of the Lambeth MS. are transposed (in an altered form) to another part of the Trinity MS. as shown in the second and first stanzas in the notes on p. 45 and p. 46. The Trin. MS. has here, for ll. 132-45, the following:</P><Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leue Chylde.</HEAD>
<L>In other mennys housys make &thorn;ou no maystry;</L>
<L>Blame &thorn;ou nat wrongfully &thorn;at &thorn;ou seest with thyne ey.</L>
<L>Dowgtyr, I pray thee, bere the so welle</L>
<L>That alle men mow sey &thorn;ou art as trew as steele:</L>
<L>A good name many folde ys more worthe then golde,</L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef Chylde.</HEAD>
<L>Be thow no chyder, ne of wordys boold</L>
<L>To myssay &thorn;y neyghbors nouther yong ne oolde;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou nat to mody ne to enuyous</L>
<L>For nought &thorn;at may betyde in o&thorn;er mennys hous:</L>
<L>An enuyous hert oft doth smert,</L>
</LG></Q></NOTE>And loke &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingis be weel whanne &thorn;ei her werkis lete,</L>
<L>And take &thorn;e keies in-to &thorn;i warde, loke &thorn;ei ben not forgete;</L>
<L>And be waar to whom &thorn;ou trustis, and spare for no qweyntise,
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>For myche harme ha&thorn; falle to them &thorn;at ben not wise;</L>
<L N="136">But, dou&yogh;tir, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be wise, &amp; do as y &thorn;ee teche,</L>
<L>And trust <MILESTONE N="109" UNIT="page">noon bettir &thorn;an &thorn;i silf, for no fair speche,</L>
<L>Mi leue childe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;eue &thorn;i meyne ther hire At &thorn;er terme day</L>
<L N="140">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ei dwelle stille or &thorn;ei wende awey,</L>
<L>Doo weel bi hem of &thorn;i good &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast in welde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an schal &thorn;ei seie weel of &thorn;ee, bo&thorn;e &thorn;e yonge and oolde;</L>
<L>&THORN;i good name is to &thorn;i freendis</L>
<L N="144">greet ioie &amp; gladnes,</L>
<L>Mi leue childe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if &thorn;i neigboris wijf ha&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue</NOTE> on riche a-tire,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore mocke &thorn;ou ne scorne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">make &thorn;ou no stryfe ne</NOTE> brenne not as fier,</L>
<L N="148">But &thorn;anke god of heuen for &thorn;at he hath &thorn;e &yogh;euene,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ou schalt, my dou&yogh;tir, a good lijf lyuande.<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyuen</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>4</SUP>he ha&thorn; eese at weelde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;anke&thorn; god feele &amp; seelde,<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>4-4</SUP> He hath esy to welde &thorn;at thanketh selde</NOTE></L>
<L N="152">Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Houswijfli &thorn;ou schalt goon on<NOTE PLACE="foot">Honestly shalt &thorn;ow go</NOTE> &thorn;e worke day [iwis,]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pride, reste, &amp; ydilnes, maki&thorn; on-&thorn;riftines;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cast hit alle away</NOTE></L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> whanne &thorn;e holi day is come, weel<NOTE PLACE="foot">clothyd honestly</NOTE> schalt &thorn;ou be</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;e holi day in<NOTE PLACE="foot">The good lord</NOTE> worschipe, &amp; god wole loue &thorn;ee;
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="44"></L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP>Haue in mynde to god is worschip [ay],</L>
<L>For myche pride come&thorn; of &thorn;e yuel day,<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>1-1</SUP> More for goddes frenshyp than the worldes worshyp</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="160">&para; <NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>Instead of lines 160-187, the Trin. Coll. MS. has the following:</P><Q><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef chylde.</HEAD>
<L>Moche shame be they worthy, &amp; sorow wolle hem betyde</L>
<L>That maketh hyr housbondes poore &thorn;orow her moche pryde.</L>
<L>Be fulle wyse, doughtyr, &amp; An howsewyfe good;</L>
<L>Aftyr the wrenne hath veynes let &thorn;ou hyr blood.</L>
<L>Hys thryft wexeth thynne &thorn;at spendeth or he wynne,</L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef chylde.</HEAD>
<L>Syt nat vp long At euyn As A gase with the cuppe</L>
<L>To sey wessayle, &amp; drynke heylle, Our syrys thryft ys vppe,</L>
<L>But go to bedde betyme, &amp; A morow ryse blyue,</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ou shalt, my leve chylde, bothe wynne &amp; thryue,</L>
<L>Alle ease may nat falle to hym &thorn;at thryue shalle,</L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef chylde.</HEAD>
<L>With ryche Roobys and garlondes, &amp; with ryche thyng,</L>
<L>Counterfete no lady as thy hosbond were a kyng.</L>
<L>With suche as he may the ayde, apayde shalt &thorn;ow be,</L>
<L>That no countenaunce be lost for cause of thee:</L>
<L>Ouyrdone pryde maketh nakyd syde, .</L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef chylde.</HEAD>
<L>Loke welle abowte; for no &thorn;yng &thorn;at &thorn;ow lete;</L>
<L>Take the keyes in to &thorn;y warde, be they nat foryete;</L>
<L>Bethynke the welle in &thorn;ought; let for no queyntyse;</L>
<L>And but yef &thorn;ow do so, &thorn;ou dost nat as the wyse.</L>
<L>For who &thorn;at loue&thorn; hym sylf best, Most may lyue in rest,</L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef chylde.</HEAD>
<L>Sorow<NOTE PLACE="foot">A mistake for 'Borow.'</NOTE> nat to blythely, ne take nat &thorn;y hyre furst,</L>
<L>But the more nede hyt make or the grettyr byrst.</L>
<L>Make the nat ryche with other mennys thyng,</L>
<L>Ne neuyr the boldyr to spende a farthyng;</L>
<L>For what soeuer &thorn;ou haue to done,</L>
<L>Borowyd thyng wylle home</L>
</LG><LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>My leef chylde.</HEAD>
<L>And yeue &thorn;y meyny her hyre at her terme day,</L>
<L>Whether they abyde stylle or wende away;</L>
<L>Yeue &thorn;ou hem of thyne owne, &amp; so wysely thee welde</L>
<L>That &thorn;y frendys haue Ioy of thee, both yong And elde:</L>
<L>Thy thryft ys &thorn;y frendes myrthe.</L>
</LG></Q></NOTE>Whanne &thorn;ou art a wijf, a nei&yogh;bore for to be,<MILESTONE N="110" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Loue &thorn;an weel &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris, as god ha&thorn; comaundide &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>It bihoue&thorn; &thorn;ee so for to do,</L>
<L>And to do to &thorn;em as &thorn;ou woldist be doon to.</L>
<L N="164">If ony discorde happen nyght or daye,</L>
<L>Make it no worse, meende it if &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if &thorn;ou schalt be a riche wijfe, Be &thorn;an not to hard,</L>
<L N="168">But weelcome faire &thorn;i neiboris &thorn;at comen to &thorn;ee warde</L>
<L>With mete, drinke, &amp; honest chere, Such as &thorn;ou maist to hem bede,</L>
<L>To ech man after his degre, &amp; help &thorn;e poore at neede;</L>
<L>and also for Hap &thorn;at may bitide,
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="45"></L>
<L N="172">Please weel &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris &thorn;at dwelle &thorn;ee biside,</L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Doughtir, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be waare, what-sum|euere &thorn;ee bitide,</L>
<L>Make not &thorn;in husbonde poore with spendinge ne with pride.</L>
<L N="176">A man must spende as he may &thorn;at ha&thorn; but easy good,</L>
<L>For aftir &thorn;e wrenne ha&thorn; veynes, Men must lete hir blood;</L>
<L>His<MILESTONE N="111" UNIT="page"> &thorn;rifte wexi&thorn; &thorn;inne</L>
<L>&THORN;at spendi&thorn; or he wynne,</L>
<L N="180">Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Borowe not to besely, nor take not &thorn;in hire first</L>
<L>But if &thorn;e more nede it make, &amp; grettir distresse;</L>
<L>Ne make &thorn;ee not to seme riche With o&thorn;er mennis &thorn;ing,
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="46"></L>
<L N="184">Ne &thorn;erfore spende neuere &thorn;e more of a ferthing;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou borowe faste,</L>
<L>It must hoome a&yogh;en at laste,</L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="188">And if &thorn;i children been<NOTE PLACE="foot">Chyldre be</NOTE> rebel, &amp; wole not hem lowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bowe</NOTE></L>
<L>If ony<NOTE PLACE="foot">any</NOTE> of hem mys doo&thorn;, nou&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">mysdo, ne</NOTE> banne hem ne blowe,</L>
<L>But take a smert rodde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yarde</NOTE> &amp; bete hem on a rowe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ei crie mercy, &amp; be of her gilt aknowe.</L>
<L N="192"><SUP>6</SUP>Leue child, by-houe&thorn; loore,</L>
<L>And euere leuer &thorn;e more,<SUP>6</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>6-6</SUP>Leue chylde behoueth lore, And euer &thorn;e leuyr the more,</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> loke to &thorn;i dou&yogh;tren<NOTE PLACE="foot">doughtres</NOTE> &thorn;at noon of hem be lorn:</L>
<L N="196">Fro &thorn;at ilk tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ei be of &thorn;ee<NOTE PLACE="foot">the</NOTE> born,</L>
<L>Bisie &thorn;ee, &amp; gadere faste towarde her mariage,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue hem to spowsynge as soone as &thorn;ei ben ablee.<NOTE PLACE="foot">be of age</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>11</SUP>Maydens ben fair &amp; amyable,</L>
<L N="200">But of her loue ful vnstable,<SUP>11</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>11-11</SUP>Maydonys be louely, but to kepe &thorn;ey be vntrusty</NOTE></L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue y &thorn;ee tau&yogh;t, dou&yogh;tir, As my modir<MILESTONE N="112" UNIT="page"> dide me;</L>
<L>&THORN;inke &thorn;eron ny&yogh;t and day, for&yogh;ete &thorn;at it not be;
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="47"></L>
<L N="204">Haue mesure and lownes, as y haue &thorn;ee tau&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted</NOTE> what man &thorn;e wedde schal, him dare care nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Betere were a child vnbore</L>
<L>&THORN;an vntau&yogh;t of wijs lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;en vntaught</NOTE></L>
<L N="208">Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now &thorn;rift and &thorn;eedom mote<NOTE PLACE="foot">the blessyng of god mot</NOTE> &thorn;ou haue, my swete barn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">baren</NOTE></L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="foot">And of</NOTE> alle oure former fadris &thorn;at euere were or aren,</L>
<L>Of alle patriarkis and prophetis &thorn;at euere weren alyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">on lyue</NOTE></L>
<L N="212">Her blessinge mote &thorn;ou haue, &amp; weel mote &thorn;ou &thorn;riue!<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Trinity MS. ends here with "My leef Chylde. Amen."</NOTE></L>
<L>For weel is &thorn;e child</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; synne wole not be filid,</L>
<L>Mi leue child.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="216">The blessynge of god mote &thorn;ou haue, and of his modir bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of alle aungils &amp; of alle archaungils, and of alle holy wight,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ou mowe haue grace to wende &thorn;e wey ful ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blis of heuene &thorn;ere sitti&thorn; god almy&yogh;t, AMEN.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000198.tif" N="48">
<HEAD>How the Wise Man tau&yogh;t His Son.<NOTE PLACE="head">[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> A.D. 1430, <I>page</I> 186.]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LIstni&thorn; lordingis, &amp; &yogh;e schulen here</L>
<L>How &thorn;e wise man tau&yogh;t his sonne,</L>
<L>And take good tent to &thorn;is matere,</L>
<L N="4">And lerne it also if &yogh;e kunne.</L>
<L>&THORN;is song was maad bi good resoun</L>
<L>To make men true and stidfast;</L>
<L>And whanne a &thorn;ing is weel bigunne,</L>
<L N="8">It maki&thorn; a good eende at &thorn;e laste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ther was a wise man tau&yogh;t his child</L>
<L>While it was &yogh;ong and tendir of age;</L>
<L>&THORN;e child was bo&thorn;e meeke &amp; myelde,</L>
<L N="12">Faire of body and of visage;</L>
<L>To leerne it hadde a good corage,</L>
<L>And to al goodnesse a greet desire;</L>
<L>With good ensaumple and faire langage</L>
<L N="16">His fadir tau&yogh;t him weel and faire,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seide, "my sonne, take good hede,</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e morewe euery day</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou do ony wordli deede,</L>
<L N="20">Lifte vp &thorn;in herte to god, &amp; pray</L>
<L>Deuoutly as &thorn;ou can or may<MILESTONE N="187" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou in grace &thorn;i lijf may lede,</L>
<L>And synne to flee bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; day,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at heuen blis may be &thorn;i mede.
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, where &thorn;at euere &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L>Be not to tale-wijs bi no wey,</L>
<L>&THORN;in owne tunge may be &thorn;i foo;</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;erfore be waar what &thorn;ou doist say,</L>
<L>Where, &amp; to whom, be ony wey,</L>
<L>Take good hede if &thorn;ou do seie ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou my&yogh;te seie a word to-day</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;at .vij. &yogh;eer after may be for-&thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, what maner man &thorn;ou be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eeue &thorn;ee not to ydilnesse,</L>
<L>But take good hede of &thorn;i degree,</L>
<L N="36">And &thorn;eron do &thorn;i bisynesse.</L>
<L>Be waar of reste and ydilnesse,</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;ingis norischen slou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>And euere be bisi more or lesse,</L>
<L N="40">It is a ful good signe of trou&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, also y waarne &thorn;ee,<MILESTONE N="188" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Desire noon office for to beere,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an it wole noon o&thorn;ir bee,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;ou muste &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris displese &amp; dere,</L>
<L>Or ellis &thorn;ou muste &thorn;i silf forswere,</L>
<L>And do not as &thorn;in office wolde,</L>
<L>And gete &thorn;ee mawgre heere &amp; &thorn;eere</L>
<L N="48">More &thorn;an &thorn;ank, an hundrid folde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, as fer as &thorn;ou may lere,</L>
<L>On yuel qwestis &thorn;ou not come,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er fals witness &thorn;ou noon bere</L>
<L N="52">On no mannys matere, al nei&thorn;er somme;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou were betere be deef &amp; dombe</L>
<L>&THORN;an falseli to go upon a qweste.</L>
<L>Sonne, &thorn;inke upon &thorn;at dreedful d&omacr;ome,</L>
<L N="56">How god schal deeme us at &thorn;e laste.
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, of oon &thorn;ing y &thorn;ee waarne,</L>
<L>And on my blessynge take good hede,</L>
<L>Be waar of vsinge of &thorn;e tauerne,</L>
<L N="60">And also &thorn;e dijs y &thorn;ee forbede,</L>
<L>And flee al letcherie in wil and dede<MILESTONE N="189" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Lest &thorn;ou come to yuel preef,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;i wittis it wole ouer lede,</L>
<L N="64">And bringe &thorn;ee into greet myscheef.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, sitte not up at euen to longe,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er vse no rere souperis late;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou be bo&thorn;e hool an strong,</L>
<L N="68">With such outrage it wole aslake;</L>
<L>And of late walking come&thorn; debate,</L>
<L>And out of tyme to sitte &amp; drink,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore be waar &amp; keep &thorn;i state,</L>
<L N="72">And go to bedde bi tyme, &amp; wynke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, if &thorn;ou wolt haue a wijf,</L>
<L>Take hir not for coueitise,</L>
<L>But wijseli enqwe&edot;re of al hir lijf,</L>
<L N="76">And take good hede, bi myn avice,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sche be meeke, curteis, and wijs;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; sche be poore, take &thorn;ou noon hede,</L>
<L>And sche wole do &thorn;ee more good seruice</L>
<L N="80">&thorn;an a riccher, whanne &thorn;ou hast neede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if &thorn;i wijf be meeke and good,<MILESTONE N="190" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And serui&thorn; &thorn;ee weel and plesauntly,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not so woode</L>
<L N="84">To charge hir to greuously;</L>
<L>But rewle &thorn;ee faire and eesili,</L>
<L>And cherische hir weel for hir good dede,</L>
<L>For ouer-doon &thorn;ing vnskilfully</L>
<L N="88">Maki&thorn; grijf to growe whanne it is no nede.
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For it is betere with reste and pees,</L>
<L>A melis meete of hoomeli fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;an for to haue an hundrid mees</L>
<L N="92">With grucchinge &amp; wi&thorn; myche care;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore leerne weel &thorn;is lore,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt haue a wijf with eese,</L>
<L>For ritchesse take hir neuere &thorn;e more</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;ou&yogh; sche wolde &thorn;ee bo&thorn;e feffe &amp; ceese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt not &thorn;i wijf displese,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er calle hir bi no vilouns name;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou do, &thorn;ou art not wijs,</L>
<L N="100">To calle hir foule it is &thorn;i schame;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou &thorn;in owne wijf wilt defame,</L>
<L>No wondir &thorn;ou&yogh; ano&thorn;ir do so,</L>
<L>But softe &amp; faire a man may tame</L>
<L N="104">Bo&thorn;e herte and hynde, bucke &amp; do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And y wole nei&thorn;ir glose ne peynt,</L>
<L>But y waarne &thorn;ee on &thorn;e o&thorn;ir side,</L>
<L>If &thorn;i wijf come wi&thorn; a playnt</L>
<L N="108">On man or child at ony tide,</L>
<L>Be not to hasti to fi&yogh;te &amp; chide,</L>
<L>And be not a-wreke til &thorn;ou know &thorn;e so&thorn;e,</L>
<L>For in wrappe &thorn;ou my&yogh;te make a braide</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at aftirwarde schulde rewe &yogh;ou bo&thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, if &thorn;ou be weel at eese,</L>
<L>And warme amonge &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris sitte,</L>
<L>Be not newfangil in no wise<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. <I>wisee</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="116">Nei&thorn;er hasti for to chaunge ne flitte,</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou do, &thorn;ou wantist witte</L>
<L>And art vnstable on euery side,</L>
<L>And also men wole speke of itt,</L>
<L N="120">And seie "&thorn;is foole can no where abide."
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sonne, &thorn;e more good &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast,<MILESTONE N="192" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ra&thorn;er here &thorn;ee meeke and lowe,</L>
<L>And booste not myche, it is but waast;</L>
<L N="124">Bi boostynge, men mowe foolis knowe.</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou paye weel &thorn;at &thorn;ou doost owe,</L>
<L>And bi o&thorn;ir richesse sette no greet price,</L>
<L>For dee&thorn; wole take bo&thorn;e hi&yogh;e and lowe,</L>
<L N="128">And &thorn;an fare-weel al &thorn;at &thorn;ere is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;erfore do &thorn;ou bi my councelle,</L>
<L>And take ensaumple of o&thorn;ir men,</L>
<L>How litil her good doo&thorn; hem a-vaile</L>
<L N="132">Whanne &thorn;ei be doluen in her den,</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at was not of hys kyn</L>
<L>Ha&thorn; his wijf, and al &thorn;at &thorn;ere is.</L>
<L>Sonne, kepe &thorn;ee out of deedly synne,</L>
<L N="136">And asaye to gete &thorn;ee paradijs,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And of &thorn;i trespas make a-meendis,</L>
<L>And to poore men of &thorn;i good &thorn;ou dele,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;i foo-men make &thorn;i freendis,</L>
<L N="140">And asaye to gete &thorn;ee soule heele,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e world is bo&thorn;e fals and freel,<MILESTONE N="193" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And euery day it doo&thorn; appaire:</L>
<L>Sonne, sette not bi &thorn;is worldis weele,</L>
<L N="144">For it fari&thorn; but as a cheri faire.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And dee&thorn; is euere, as y trowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e moost certeyn &thorn;ing &thorn;at is,</L>
<L>And no &thorn;ing is so vncerteyn to knowe</L>
<L N="148">As is &thorn;e tyme of dee&thorn; y-wis:</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore my sonne, &thorn;inke on &thorn;is</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;at y haue seid biforn,</L>
<L>And ihesu bringe us to his blis</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at for vs bare &thorn;e crowne of &thorn;orn! Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="item">

<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="53">
<HEAD>Recipes. [<I>From Harleian MS.</I> 5401, <I>ab.</I> 1480-1500 A.D.]</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="recipe">
<HEAD>FRUTURS. (<MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="page"> or <MILESTONE N="69b" UNIT="folio">)</HEAD>
<P>Recipe &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">The &thorn; is always y in Harl. 5401.</NOTE> cromys of whyte brede, &amp; swete apyls, &amp; &yogh;okkis of eggis, &amp; bray &thorn;am wele, &amp; temper it with wyne, &amp; make it to sethe; &amp; when it is thyk, do &thorn;er-to gode spyces, gynger &amp; galingay &amp; canyll &amp; clows, &amp; serve it forthe. (See also <I>Liber Cure Cocorum</I>, p. 39-40.)</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="recipe">
<HEAD>FRUTURS OF FYGIS. (<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="page"> or <MILESTONE N="98a" UNIT="folio">)</HEAD>
<P>Recipe &amp; make bature of floure, ale, peper &amp; saferon, with o&thorn;er spices; &thorn;an cast &thorn;am<NOTE PLACE="foot">that is, the figs.</NOTE> in to a frying pann with batur, &amp; ole, &amp; bake &thorn;am &amp; serve. (See another recipe in <I>Household Ordinances</I>, p. 450, under the head "Turtelettys of Fruture.")</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="recipe">
<HEAD>IUSSELL. (<MILESTONE N="198" UNIT="page"> or <MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio">)</HEAD>
<P>Recipe brede gratyd, &amp; eggis; &amp; swyng &thorn;am to-gydere, &amp; do &thorn;erto sawge, &amp; saferon, &amp; salt; &thorn;an take gode brothe, &amp; cast it &thorn;er-to, &amp; bole it enforesayd, &amp; do &thorn;er-to as to charlete &amp;c. (See also <I>Liber Cure Cocorum</I>, p. 11; Jussel of Flesh, <I>Household Ordinances</I>, p. 462; Jussel enforsed, p. 463; Jussel of Fysshe, p. 469.)</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="recipe">
<HEAD>MAWMENY. (<MILESTONE N="201" UNIT="page"> or <MILESTONE N="100a" UNIT="folio">)</HEAD>
<P>Recipe brawne of Capons or of hennys, &amp; dry &thorn;am wele, &amp; towse &thorn;am smalle; &thorn;an take thyk mylk of almonds, &amp; put &thorn;e saide brawn &thorn;er-to, &amp; styr it wele ouer &thorn;e fyre, &amp; seson it with suger, &amp; powder of Canelle, with mase, quibibs, &amp; anneys in confete, &amp; serve it forthe. (See also the recipe "For to make momene" in <I>Liber Cure Cocorum</I>, p. 26; for "Mawmene for xl. Mees" in <I>Household Ordinances</I>, p. 455; and "Mawmene to Potage," p. 430.)</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="recipe">
<HEAD>FRETOURE. (<I>Harl. MS.</I> 276.)</HEAD>
<P><NOTE PLACE="marg">Vyaunde leche. L.iiii.</NOTE><B>Fretoure.</B> Take whete Floure, Ale, &YOGH;est, Safroun, &amp; Salt, &amp; bete alle to-gederys as &thorn;ikke as &thorn;ou schuldyst make o&thorn;er bature in fleyssche tyme, &amp; &thorn;an take fayre Applys, &amp; kut hem in maner of Fretourys, &amp; wete hem in &thorn;e bature vp on downe, &amp; frye hem in fayre Oyle, &amp; caste hem in a dyssche, &amp; caste Sugre &thorn;er-on, &amp; serue forth. [The recipe for "Tansye" is No. l. vi.]</P>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">


<DIV2 TYPE="Middle English version"><PB REF="00000204.tif" N="54">
<HEAD>A Diatorie. [<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 182.]</HEAD>
<ARGUMENT><P>To be rulid bi &thorn;is diatorie do &thorn;i diligence, For it techi&thorn; good diete &amp; good gouernaunce.</P></ARGUMENT>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(I. LATIN II.)</HEAD>
<L>IF so be &thorn;at lechis doon &thorn;ee faile,</L>
<L>Vse good diete bi &thorn;e councel of me,&mdash;</L>
<L>Mesurable fedyng and temperat trauaile,&mdash;</L>
<L N="4">And be not maliciose for noon aduersite,</L>
<L>But be meeke in trouble, glad in pouerte,</L>
<L>Not pensif ne &thorn;ou&yogh;tful for ony sodein chaunce,</L>
<L>Not grutchinge, but myrie aftir &thorn;i degree.</L>
<L N="8">If fisijk lacke, make &thorn;is &thorn;i gouernaunce,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(II. LATIN I.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Kepe from colde &thorn;i feet, &thorn;i stomak, &amp; &thorn;in heed;<MILESTONE N="183" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Ete no raw mete, take good hede &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>Drinke holsum drinke, &amp; feede &thorn;ee on li&yogh;t breed,</L>
<L N="12">&amp; with an appitid from &thorn;i mete looke &thorn;at &thorn;ou goo.</L>
<L>Lede &thorn;i lijf in chastite, &thorn;ou schalt finde it best so;</L>
<L>Drinke not vpon &thorn;i sleep, but do as y &thorn;ee teche,</L>
<L>And bere no wra&thorn;&thorn;e to freende ne to foo;</L>
<L N="16">vse not to soupe late, ne to drinke myche.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(III. LATIN IV.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Digne not on &thorn;e morewe to-fore &thorn;in appitide;</L>
<L>Cleer eir &amp; walking maki&thorn; good digestioun.
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>Drinke not bitwene melis for no froward delite</L>
<L N="20">But if &thorn;urst or traueile &yogh;eue &thorn;ee occasioun.</L>
<L>And ouer salt mete doo&thorn; greet oppressioun</L>
<L>To feble stomakis &thorn;at wole not hem refreyne</L>
<L>From &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben contrarie to her complex|ioun,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;ei doon to her stomakis ofte myche peine.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(IV. LATIN VII.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Vse no surfetis nei&thorn;ir day ne nyght,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er ony rere soupers, which is but excesse;</L>
<L>And be waar of nodding heedis &amp; of candil li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="28">And also of long sleep and of ydilnesse</L>
<L>&para; The which of alle vicis sche is porteresse.<MILESTONE N="184" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And voide alle drunkelew folk, liers, &amp; letchouris,</L>
<L>And alle hem &thorn;at vsen suche vn&thorn;riftynesse,</L>
<L N="32">And also dijs pleiers and hacerdouris.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(V. LATIN III.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; To yuel talis &yogh;eeue noo credence;</L>
<L>Be not to hasti, ne to sodeyn veniable;</L>
<L>To poore folk do &thorn;ou no violence;</L>
<L N="36">Be gentil of langage, in fedinge mesurable;</L>
<L>On sundri metis be not gredi at &thorn;e table;</L>
<L>Long sleep aftir mete doo&thorn; myche greuaunce.</L>
<L>Blame no condicioun which is commendable;</L>
<L N="40">But to seie &thorn;e beste, sette alle &thorn;i plesaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(VI. LATIN VI.)</HEAD>
<L>Use fier bi &thorn;e morewe, &amp; to bedward at eue</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens blake mystis and eir of pestilence;</L>
<L>And arise &thorn;ou eerli if &thorn;ou be in heele,</L>
<L N="44">And first bi &thorn;e morewe do god reuerence.</L>
<L>To visite &thorn;e poore do &thorn;i diligence,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e needi haue compassioun,
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="58"></L>
<L>For good deedis causi&thorn; mir&thorn;e in conscience,</L>
<L N="48">And in heuene to haue greet possessioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(VII. LATIN V.)</HEAD>
<L>Be not nyce in clo&thorn;inge passing &thorn;in astate;<MILESTONE N="185" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Be rewlid bi temperaunce while &thorn;ou art a-lyue;</L>
<L>And with .iij. maner of folk be not at debate:</L>
<L N="52">First with &thorn;i bettir be waar for to stryue,</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;i felaw noo quarel &thorn;ou contryue,</L>
<L>With &thorn;i suget to stryue, it is but schame;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore y councelle &thorn;ee, while &thorn;ou art a-liue,</L>
<L N="56">To liue in pees, and gete &thorn;ee a good name.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(VIII. LATIN X.)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In two &thorn;ingis stondi&thorn; a mannis wel&thorn;e,</L>
<L>In soule &amp; bodi, who-so wole hem sewe,</L>
<L>Mesurable fedinge kepi&thorn; a man in hel&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="60">And ri&yogh;t so is charite to &thorn;e soule dewe.</L>
<L>For&yogh;ete not &thorn;is diete, for it is good &amp; trewe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; it be bou&yogh;t of no potecarie</L>
<L>Ne of noon o&thorn;er maister &thorn;at greet cunnynge can schewe,</L>
<L N="64">&YOGH;it y councelle &thorn;ee, be dietid bi &thorn;is diatorie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(IX.)</HEAD>
<L>Serue &yogh;e god deuoutly</L>
<L>And &thorn;e world truly,</L>
<L>Ete &yogh;e &yogh;oure mete mirili</L>
<L>and euere liue &yogh;e in reste.</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;anke &yogh;e euere god hy&yogh;li;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;at &yogh;e liue here poreli,</L>
<L>He may amende it li&yogh;tly</L>
<L>whanne him liki&thorn; beste.<NOTE PLACE="end">[A different and later version of this Poem was printed by Mr Halliwell from MS. Harl. 2251, fol. 4-5, in his <I>Selection from the Minor Poems of Dan John Lydgate</I> for the Percy Society, 1840, pp. 66-69. He remarks that the "poem is very common in manu|script, but several of the copies vary considerably from each other. It may be sufficient to refer to MS. Harl. 116, fol. 116; MS. Oxon. Bernard. 1479; MS. Rawl. Oxon. C. 86; MS. Arund. 168; MS. Sloan. 775; and MS. Sloan. 3554, which contains a Latin version. Ritson has inserted this in his list of Lydgate's works in two places, under Nos. 55 and 61." Harl. 5401 contains a late copy.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
