<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1125">&para; hit rebuketh not a knyght / &thorn;e knyges grome to sytte at his table,</L>
<L>no more hit dothe a mershalle of maners plesable;</L>
<L>and so from &thorn;e hiest degre / to &thorn;e lowest honor|able,</L>
<L N="1128">if &thorn;e mershalle haue a sight &thorn;erto, he is com|mendable.
<PB REF="00000348.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>&para; Wisdom wolle a mershalle manerabely &thorn;at he vndirstand</L>
<L>alle &thorn;e worshipfulle officers of the comunialte of &thorn;is land,</L>
<L>of Shires / Citees / borowes; like as &thorn;ey ar ruland,</L>
<L N="1132">&thorn;ey must be sett aftur &thorn;eire astate dewe in degre as &thorn;ey stand.</L>
<L>&para; hit belongethe to a mershalle to haue a fore sight</L>
<L>of alle estatis of &thorn;is land in euery place pight,<MILESTONE N="188a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For &thorn;estate of a knyght of blode, lyvelode, &amp; myght,</L>
<L N="1136">is not peregalle to a symple &amp; a poouere knyght.</L>
<L>&para; Also &thorn;e meyre of london, notable of dignyte,</L>
<L>and of queneborow<NOTE PLACE="foot">Queenborough, an ancient, but poor town of Kent, in the Isle of Sheppey, situated at the mouth of the river Medway. The chief employment of the inhabitants is oyster-dredging. <I>Walker's Gazeteer, by Kershaw</I>, 1801.</NOTE> &thorn;e meire, no &thorn;ynge like in degre,</L>
<L>at one messe &thorn;ey owght in no wise to sitt ne be;</L>
<L N="1140">hit no &thorn;ynge besemethe / &thorn;erfore to suche semble ye se /</L>
<L>&para; Also &thorn;e abbote of Westmynstere, &thorn;e hiest of &thorn;is lande /</L>
