<L>And &thorn;e prioure of Dudley,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dudley, a town of Worcestershire, insulated in Staffordshire, containing about 2000 families, most of whom are employed in the manufacture of nails and other iron wares. <I>Walker</I>, 1801.</NOTE> no &thorn;ynge so digne as he:&mdash;</L>
<L>&yogh;et may not &thorn;e prioure of dudley, symple of degre,</L>
<L N="1148">Sitte with &thorn;e prioure of Caunturbury: &thorn;er is why, a dyuersite.</L>
<L>&para; And remembre euermore / an rule &thorn;er is generalle:</L>
<L>A prioure &thorn;at is a prelate of any churche Cathe|dralle,</L>
<L>above abbot or prioure with-in the diocise sitte he shalle,</L>
<L N="1152">In churche / in chapelle / in chambur / &amp; in halle.</L>
<L>&para; Right so reuerend docturs, degre of xij. yere, &thorn;em ye must assigne</L>
<L>to sitte aboue hym / &thorn;at commensed hath but .ix.</L>
<L>and &thorn;aughe &thorn;e yonger may larger spend gold red &amp; fyne,</L>
<L N="1156">&yogh;et shalle &thorn;e eldur sitte aboue / whe&thorn;ur he drynke or dyne.</L>
<L>&para; like wise the aldremen, &yogh;ef &thorn;ey be eny where,
<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>&thorn;e yongere shalle sitte or stande benethe &thorn;e elder ri&yogh;t &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>and of euery crafft &thorn;e mastir aftur rule &amp; manere,</L>
<L N="1160">and &thorn;en &thorn;e eldest of &thorn;em, &thorn;at warden was &thorn;e fore yere.</L>
<L>&para; Soche poyntes, with many o&thorn;er, belongethe to a mershall;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore whensoeuer youre sovereyn a feest make shall,</L>
<L>demeene what estates shalle sitte in the hall,</L>
<L N="1164">&thorn;an reson with youre self lest youre lord yow calle;</L>
<L>&para; Thus may ye devise youre marshallynge, like as y yow lere,</L>
<L>to &thorn;e honoure and worshippe of youre souereyn euery where;</L>
<L>And &yogh;eff ye haue eny dowt / euer looke &thorn;at ye enquere,</L>
<L N="1168">Resorte euer to youre souereyne / or to &thorn;e cheff officere;</L>
<L>&para; Thus shalle ye to any state / do wronge ne pre|iudice,</L>
<L>to sette euery persone accordynge with-owten mys,</L>
<L>as aftur &thorn;e birthe / livelode / dignite / a-fore y taught yow this,</L>
<L N="1172">alle degrees of highe officere, &amp; worthy as he is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now good son, y haue shewed the / &amp; brought &thorn;e in vre,</L>
<L>to know &thorn;e Curtesie of court / &amp; these &thorn;ow may take in cure,</L>
<L>In pantry / botery / or cellere / &amp; in kervynge a-fore a sovereyne demewre,</L>
<L N="1176">A sewer / or a mershalle: in &thorn;es science / y sup|pose ye byn sewre,
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>&para; Which in my dayes y lernyd withe a prynce fulle royalle,</L>
<L>with whom vschere in chambur was y, &amp; mer|shalle also in halle,</L>
<L>vnto whom alle &thorn;ese officeres foreseid / &thorn;ey euer entende shalle,</L>
<L N="1180">Evir to fulfille my commaundement when &thorn;at y to &thorn;em calle:</L>
<L>For we may allow &amp; dissalow / oure office is &thorn;e cheeff</L>
<L>In cellere &amp; spicery / &amp; the Cooke, be he loothe or leeff.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Two lines are wanting here to make up the stanza. They must have been left out when the copier turned his page, and began again.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus &thorn;e diligences of dyuerse office&yogh; y haue shewed to &thorn;e allone,<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1184">the which science may be shewed &amp; doon by a syngeler<NOTE PLACE="foot">The word in the MS. is <I>syngle</I> or <I>synglr</I> with a line through the <I>l</I>. It may be for synguler, <I>singulus, i. unus per se</I>, sunderly, vocab. in <I>Rel. Ant</I>. v. 1, p. 9, col. 1.</NOTE> persone;</L>
<L>but &thorn;e dignyte of a prince requirethe vche office must haue oon</L>
<L>to be rewlere in his rome / a seruaund hym waytynge on.</L>
<L>&para; Moore-ouer hit requirethe euerich of &thorn;em in office to haue perfite science,</L>
<L N="1188">For dowt and drede doynge his souereyn dis|plicence,</L>
<L>hym to attende, and his gestis to plese in place where &thorn;ey ar presence,</L>
<L>that his souereyn &thorn;roughe his seruice may make grete congaudence.</L>
<L>&para; For a prynce to serue, ne dowt he not / and god be his spede!
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="196"></L>
<L N="1192">Fur&thorn;er &thorn;an his office / &amp; &thorn;er-to let hym take good hede,</L>
<L>and his warde wayte wisely // &amp; euermore &thorn;er-in haue drede;</L>
<L>&THORN;us doynge his dewte dewly, to dowte he shalle not nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Tastynge and credence<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Credence</I> as <I>creance</I> . . a taste or essay taken of another man's meat. Cotgrave.</NOTE> longethe to blode &amp; birth royalle,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>Compare <I>The Boke of Curtasye</I>, below, l. 495-8,</P><Q><L>No mete for mon schalle sayed be</L><L>Bot for kynge or prynce or duke so fre;</L><L>For heiers of paraunce also y-wys</L><L>Mete shalle be seyed.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L N="1196">As pope / emperoure / Emperatrice, and Car|dynalle,</L>
<L>kynge / queene / prynce / Archebischoppe in palle,</L>
<L>Duke / Erle, and no mo / &thorn;at y to remembraunce / calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Credence is vsed, &amp; tastynge, for drede of poy|senynge,</L>
<L N="1200">To alle officers y-sworne / and grete othe by chargynge;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore vche man in office kepe his rome sewre, closynge</L>
<L>Cloos howse / chest / &amp; gardevyan<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Gardmanger</I> (Fr.) a Storehouse for meat. Blount, ed. 1681, <I>Garde-viant</I>, a Wallet for a Soldier to put his Victuals in. Phillipps, ed. 1701.</NOTE>, for drede of congettynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Steward and Chamburlayn of a prince of royalte,</L>
<L N="1204">&thorn;ey haue / knowleche of homages, seruice, and fewte;</L>
<L>so &thorn;ey haue ouersight of euery office / aftur &thorn;eire degre,
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="197"></L>
<L>by wrytynge &thorn;e knowleche / &amp; &thorn;e Credence to ouerse;</L>
<L>&para; Therfore in makynge of his credence, it is to drede, y sey,</L>
<L N="1208">To mershalle / sewere<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Boke of Curtasye makes the Sewer alone assay or taste 'alle the mete' (l. 763-76), and the Butler the drink (l. 786, below).</NOTE> and kervere &thorn;ey must allowte allwey,</L>
<L>to teche hym of his office / &thorn;e credence hym to prey:</L>
<L>&thorn;us shalle he not stond in makynge of his cre|dence in no fray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Moore of &thorn;is connynge y Cast not me to con|treve:</L>
<L N="1212">my tyme is not to tary, hit drawest fast to eve.</L>
<L>&thorn;is tretyse &thorn;at y haue entitled, if it ye entende to preve,</L>
<L>y assayed me self in youthe with-outen any greve.</L>
<L>while y was yonge y-noughe &amp; lusty in dede,</L>
<L N="1216">y enioyed &thorn;ese maters foreseid / &amp; to lerne y toke good hede;</L>
<L>but croked age hathe compelled me / &amp; leue court y must nede.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore, sone, assay thy self / &amp; god shalle be &thorn;y spede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Now feire falle yow, fadur / &amp; blessid mote ye be,</L>
<L N="1220">For &thorn;is comenynge / &amp; &thorn;e connynge / &thorn;at y[e] haue here shewed me!</L>
<L>now dar y do seruice diligent / to dyuers of dignyte,</L>
<L>where for scantnes of connynge y durst no man y-se.
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>So perfitely sethe y hit perceue / my parte y wolle preue and assay;<MILESTONE N="189a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1224">bo&thorn;e by practike and exercise / yet som good lerne y may:</L>
<L>and for youre gentille lernynge / y am bound euer to pray</L>
<L>that oure lorde rewarde you in blis that lasteth aye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Now, good son, thy self with other &thorn;at shalle &thorn;e succede,</L>
<L N="1228">whiche &thorn;us boke of nurture shalle note / lerne, &amp; ouer rede,<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>Boke of Nurture,</I></NOTE></L>
<L>pray for the sowle of Iohn Russelle, &thorn;at god do hym mede,</L>
<L>Som tyme seruaunde with duke vmfrey, duc<NOTE PLACE="foot">The <I>duc</I> has a red stroke through it, probably to cut it out.</NOTE> of Glowcetur in dede.</L>
<L>For &thorn;at prynce pereles prayethe / &amp; for suche other mo,</L>
<L N="1232">&thorn;e sowle of my wife / my fadur and modir also, vn-to Mary modyr and mayd / she fende us from owre foe,</L>
<L>and brynge vs alle to blis when we shalle hens goo.</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN."</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>GO forthe lytelle boke, and lowly &thorn;ow me commende</L>
<L N="1236">vnto alle yonge gentilmen / &thorn;at lust to lerne or entende,</L>
<L>and specially to &thorn;em &thorn;at han exsperience, praynge &thorn;e[m] to amende</L>
<L>and correcte &thorn;at is amysse, &thorn;ere as y fawte or offende.</L>
<L>&para; And if so &thorn;at any be founde / as &thorn;rou&yogh; myn necligence,
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="199"></L>
<L N="1240">Cast &thorn;e cawse on my copy / rude / &amp; bare of eloquence,</L>
<L>whiche to drawe out [I] haue do my besy dili|gence,</L>
<L>redily to reforme hit / by reson and bettur sentence.</L>
<L>&para; As for ryme or reson, &thorn;e forewryter was not to blame,</L>
<L N="1244">For as he founde hit aforne hym, so wrote he &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>and &thorn;aughe he or y in oure matere digres or degrade,</L>
<L>blame neithur of vs / For we neuyre hit made;</L>
<L>&para; Symple as y had insight / somwhat &thorn;e ryme y correcte;</L>
<L N="1248">blame y cowde no man / y haue no persone sus|pecte.</L>
<L>Now, good god, graunt vs grace / oure sowles neuer to Infecte!</L>
<L>&thorn;an may we regne in &thorn;i regioun / eternally with thyne electe.<NOTE PLACE="end">[Some word or words in large black letter have been cut off at the bottom of the page.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
