<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000458.tif">

<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="[299]">
<HEAD>The boke of Curtasye.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="book">
<HEAD>HEre begynnethe &thorn;e fyrst boke of curtasye.<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Qwo so wylle of curtasy lere,</L>
<L>In this boke he may hit here!</L>
<L>Yf thow be gentylmon, &yogh;omon, or knaue,</L>
<L N="4">The nedis nurture for to haue.</L>
<L>When thou comes to a lordis &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>The porter &thorn;ou shalle fynde ther-ate;</L>
<L>Take hym thow shalt &thorn;y wepyn tho,</L>
<L N="8">And aske hym leue in to go</L>
<L>&para; To speke with lorde, lady, squyer, or grome.</L>
<L>Ther-to the nedys to take the tome<NOTE PLACE="foot">Toom or rymthe. <I>Spacium, tempus, oportunitas</I>. P. Parv.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>For yf he be of loghe degre,</L>
<L N="12">Than hym falles to come to the;</L>
<L>&para; Yf he be gentylmon of kyn,</L>
<L>The porter wille lede the to hym.</L>
<L>When thow come tho halle dor to,</L>
<L N="16">Do of thy hode, thy gloues also;</L>
<L>&para; Yf &thorn;o halle be at the furst mete,</L>
<L>This lessoun loke thow no&yogh;t for-&yogh;ete:</L>
<L>&THORN;e stuard, countroller, and tresurere,</L>
<L N="20">Sittand at de deshe, &thorn;ou haylse in fere.</L>
<L>&para; Within &thorn;e halle sett on ayther side,</L>
<L>Sitten other gentylmen as falles &thorn;at tyde;</L>
<L>Enclyne &thorn;e fayre to hom also,</L>
<L N="24">First to the ry&yogh;ht honde &thorn;ou shalle go,
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="300"></L>
<L>&para; Sitthen to &thorn;o left honde &thorn;y neghe &thorn;ou cast;</L>
<L>To hom &thorn;ou boghe withouten wrast<NOTE PLACE="foot">AS. <I>wr&aelig;sten</I>, to writhe, twist.</NOTE>;</L>
<L>Take hede to &yogh;omon on &thorn;y ryght honde,</L>
<L N="28">And sithen byfore the screne &thorn;ou stonde</L>
<L>&para; In myddys &thorn;e halle opon &thorn;e flore,</L>
<L>Whille marshalle or vssher come fro &thorn;e dore,</L>
<L>And bydde the sitte, or to borde the lede.</L>
<L N="32">Be stabulle of chere for menske<NOTE PLACE="foot">grace, civility; from AS. <I>mennisc</I>, human; cp. our double sense of <I>humanity</I>. H. Coleridge.</NOTE>, y rede;</L>
<L>&para; Yf he &thorn;e sette at gentilmonnes borde,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou be hynde<NOTE PLACE="foot">courteous.</NOTE> and lytulle of worde.</L>
<L>Pare &thorn;y brede and kerue in two,</L>
<L N="36">Tho ouer crust &thorn;o nether fro;</L>
<L>&para; In fowre &thorn;ou kutt &thorn;o ouer dole,</L>
<L>Sett hom to-gedur as hit where hole;</L>
<L>Sithen kutt &thorn;o nether crust in thre,</L>
<L N="40">And turnc hit down, lerne &thorn;is at me.</L>
<L>&para; And lay thy trenchour &thorn;e be-fore,</L>
<L>And sitt vp-ry&yogh;ht for any sore.</L>
<L>Spare brede or wyne, drynke or ale,</L>
<L N="44">To thy messe of kochyn be sett in sale;</L>
<L>&para; Lest men sayne &thorn;ou art hongur betcn,</L>
<L>Or ellis a gloten &thorn;at alle men wyten,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;y naylys ben clene in blythe,</L>
<L N="48">Lest &thorn;y felaghe lothe ther-wyth.</L>
<L>&para; Byt not on thy brede and lay hit doun,&mdash;</L>
<L>That is no curteyse to vse in town;&mdash;</L>
<L>But breke as myche as &thorn;ou wylle ete,</L>
<L N="52">The remelant to pore &thorn;ou shalle lete.</L>
<L>&para; In peese &thorn;ou ete, and euer eschewe</L>
<L>To flyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">AS. <I>flytan</I>, dispute, quarrel.</NOTE> at borde; &thorn;at may &thorn;e rewe.</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou make mawes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mowe, or skorne. <I>Vangia, vel valgia, cachinna</I>. Promptorium.</NOTE> on any wyse,</L>
<L N="56">A velany &thorn;ou kacches or euer &thorn;ou rise.
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="301"></L>
<L>&para; Let neuer &thorn;y cheke be Made to grete<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>With morselle of brede &thorn;at &thorn;ou shalle ete;</L>
<L>An apys mow men sayne he makes,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at brede and flesshe in hys cheke bakes.</L>
<L>&para; Yf any man speke &thorn;at tyme to the,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalle onsware, hit wille not be</L>
<L>But waloande, and a-byde &thorn;ou most;</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;at is a schame for alle the host.</L>
<L>&para; On bothe halfe &thorn;y mouthe, yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou ete,</L>
<L>Mony a skorne shalle &thorn;ou gete.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou shalle not lau&yogh;he ne speke no &thorn;ynge</L>
<L N="68">Whille &thorn;i mouthe be fulle of mete or drynke;</L>
<L>&para; Ne suppe not with grete sowndynge</L>
<L>No&thorn;er potage ne o&thorn;er &thorn;ynge.</L>
<L>Let not &thorn;i spone stond in &thorn;y dysche,</L>
<L N="72">Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou be serued with fleshe or fische;</L>
<L>&para; Ne lay hit not on thy dishe syde,</L>
<L>But clense hit honestly with-outen pride.</L>
<L>Loke no browynge on &thorn;y fyngur &thorn;ore</L>
<L N="76">Defoule &thorn;e clothe &thorn;e be-fore.</L>
<L>&para; In &thorn;i dysche yf &thorn;ou wete &thorn;y brede,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;er-of &thorn;at no&yogh;t be lede</L>
<L>To cast agayne &thorn;y dysche in-to;</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ou art vn-hynde yf &thorn;ou do so.</L>
<L>&para; Drye &thorn;y mouthe ay wele and fynde</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou schalle drynke o&thorn;er ale or wyne.</L>
<L>Ne calle &thorn;ou no&yogh;t a dysche a-&yogh;ayne,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at ys take fro &thorn;e borde in playne;</L>
<L>&para; &yogh;if &thorn;ou sp[i]tt ouer the borde, or elles opon,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalle be holden an vncurtayse mon;</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;y nown dogge &thorn;ou scrape or clawe,</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at is holden a vyse emong men knawe.</L>
<L>&para; Yf &thorn;y nose &thorn;ou clense, as may be-falle,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;y honde &thorn;ou clense, as wythe-alle,</L>
<L>Priuely with skyrt do hit away,</L>
<L N="92">O&thorn;er ellis thurghe thi tepet &thorn;at is so gay.
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="302"></L>
<L>&para; Clense not thi tethe at mete sittande,</L>
<L>With knyfe ne stre, styk ne wande.</L>
<L>While &thorn;ou holdes mete in mouthe, be war</L>
<L N="96">To drynke, &thorn;at is an-honest<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>an</I> privative, unhonest.</NOTE> char,</L>
<L>&para; And also fysike for-bedes hit,</L>
<L>And sais &thorn;ou may be choket at &thorn;at byt;</L>
<L>Yf hit go &thorn;y wrang throte into,</L>
<L N="100">And stoppe &thorn;y wynde, &thorn;ou art fordo.</L>
<L>&para; Ne telle &thorn;ou neuer at borde no tale</L>
<L>To harme or shame &thorn;y felawe in sale;</L>
<L>For if he then withholde his methe<NOTE PLACE="foot">AS. <I>mod</I>, mood, passion, violence.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="104">Eftsons he wylle forcast &thorn;i dethe.</L>
<L>&para; Where-sere &thorn;ou sitt at mete in borde,</L>
<L>Avoide &thorn;e cat at on bare worde,</L>
<L>For yf &thorn;ou stroke cat o&thorn;er dogge,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;ou art lyke an ape tey&yogh;ed with a clogge.</L>
<L>&para; Also eschewe, with-outen stryfe,</L>
<L>To foule &thorn;e borde clothe with &thorn;i knyfe;</L>
<L>Ne blow not on &thorn;y drynke ne mete,</L>
<L N="112">Ne&thorn;er for colde, ne&thorn;er for hete;</L>
<L>&para; With mete ne bere &thorn;y knyfe to mowthe,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou be sett be strong or couthe;</L>
<L>Ne with &thorn;o borde clothe &thorn;i tethe &thorn;ou wype,<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="116">Ne &thorn;y nyen &thorn;at rennen rede, as may betyde.</L>
<L>&para; Yf &thorn;ou sitt by a ry&yogh;ht good man,</L>
<L>&THORN;is lesson loke &thorn;ou &thorn;enke apon:</L>
<L>Vndur his the&yogh;ghe &thorn;y kne not pit,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;ou ar fulle lewed yf &thorn;ou dose hit.</L>
<L>&para; Ne bacwarde sittande gyf no&yogh;t &thorn;y cupe,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er to drynke, no&thorn;er to suppe;</L>
<L>Bidde &thorn;i frende take cuppe and drynke,</L>
<L N="124">&THORN;at is holden an honest thyng.</L>
<L>&para; Lene not on elbowe at &thorn;y mete,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er for colde ne for hete;
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="303"></L>
<L>Dip not &thorn;i thombe &thorn;y drynke into,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;ou art vncurtayse yf &thorn;ou hit do;</L>
<L>&para; In salt saler yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou pit</L>
<L>O&thorn;er fisshe or flesshe &thorn;at men may wyt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is a vyce, as men me telles,</L>
<L N="132">And gret wonder hit most be elles.</L>
<L>&para; After mete when &thorn;ou shalt wasshe,</L>
<L>Spitt not in basyn, ne water &thorn;ou dasshe;</L>
<L>Ne spit not lorely, for no kyn mede,</L>
<L N="136">Be-fore no mon of god for drede.</L>
<L>&para; Who so euer despise &thorn;is lessoun ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>At borde to sitt he hase no my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Here endys now oure fyrst talkyng,</L>
<L N="140">Crist graunt vs alle his dere blessyng!</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>&para; Here endithe &thorn;e [first] boke of curtasye.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="book">
<HEAD>THE SECOND BOOK.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>YF that &thorn;ou be a &yogh;ong enfaunt,</L>
<L>And thenke &thorn;o scoles for to haunt,</L>
<L>This lessoun schalle &thorn;y maistur &thorn;e merke,</L>
<L N="144">Croscrist &thorn;e spede in alle &thorn;i werke;</L>
<L>Sytthen &thorn;y <I>pater</I> noster he wille &thorn;e teche,</L>
<L>As cristes owne postles con preche;</L>
<L>Aftur &thorn;y Aue maria and &thorn;i crede,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at shalle &thorn;e saue at dome of drede;</L>
<L>&para; Then aftur to blesse &thorn;e with &thorn;e trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>In nomine patris teche he wille &thorn;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;en with marke, mathew, luke, and Ion,</L>
<L N="152">With &thorn;e per crucis and the hegh name;</L>
<L>&para; To schryue &thorn;e in general &thorn;ou schalle lere</L>
<L>&THORN;y Confiteor and misereatur in fere.
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="304"></L>
<L>To seche &thorn;e kyngdam of god, my chylde,</L>
<L N="156">&THORN;erto y rede &thorn;ou be not wylde.</L>
<L>&para; Ther-fore worschip god, bothe olde and &yogh;ong,</L>
<L>To be in body and soule yliche stronge.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou comes to &thorn;o chirche dore,</L>
<L N="160">Take &thorn;e haly water stondand on flore;</L>
<L>&para; Rede or synge or byd prayeris</L>
<L>To crist, for alle &thorn;y crysten ferys;</L>
<L>Be curtayse to god, and knele doun</L>
<L N="164">On bothe knees with grete deuocioun.</L>
<L>&para; To mon &thorn;ou shalle knele opon &thorn;e ton,</L>
<L>&THORN;e to&thorn;er to &thorn;y self &thorn;ou halde alon.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou ministers at &thorn;e heghe autere,</L>
<L N="168">With bothe hondes &thorn;ou serue &thorn;o prest in fere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ton to stabulle &thorn;e to&thorn;er</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;ou fayle, my dere bro&thorn;er.</L>
<L>&para; Ano&thorn;er curtayse y wylle &thorn;e teche,</L>
<L N="172">Thy fadur And modur, with mylde speche,<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In worschip and serue with alle &thorn;y my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dwelle &thorn;e lengur in erthely ly&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; To ano&thorn;er man do no more amys</L>
<L N="176">Then &thorn;ou woldys be don of hym and hys;</L>
<L>So crist &thorn;ou pleses, and getes &thorn;e loue</L>
<L>Of men and god &thorn;at syttis aboue.</L>
<L>&para; Be not to meke, but in mene &thorn;e holde,</L>
<L N="180">For ellis a fole &thorn;ou wylle be tolde.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at to ry&yogh;twysnes wylle enclyne,</L>
<L>As holy wry&yogh;t says vs wele and fyne,</L>
<L>His sede schalle neuer go seche hor brede,</L>
<L N="184">Ne suffur of mon no shames dede.</L>
<L>&para; To for-gyf &thorn;ou shalle &thorn;e hast;</L>
<L>To veniaunce loke &thorn;ou come on last;</L>
<L>Draw &thorn;e to pese with alle &thorn;y streng&thorn;e;</L>
<L N="188">Fro stryf and bate draw &thorn;e on leng&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&para; Yf mon aske &thorn;e good for goddys sake,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wont thynge wher-of to take,
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="305"></L>
<L>Gyf hym boner wordys on fayre manere,</L>
<L N="192">With glad semblaunt<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. semblamt]</NOTE> and pure good cher.</L>
<L>&para; Also of seruice &thorn;ou shalle be fre</L>
<L>To euery mon in hys degr&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalle neuer lose for to be kynde;</L>
<L N="196">That on for&yogh;etis ano&thorn;er hase in mynde.</L>
<L>&para; Yf Any man haue part with &thorn;e in gyft,</L>
<L>With hym &thorn;ou make an euen skyft;</L>
<L>Let hit not henge in honde for glose,</L>
<L N="200">&THORN;ou art vncurtayse yf &thorn;ou hyt dose.</L>
<L>&para; To sayntis yf &thorn;ou &thorn;y gate hase hy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Thou schalle fulfylle hit with alle &thorn;y my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Lest god &thorn;e stryk with grete veniaunce,</L>
<L N="204">And pyt &thorn;e in-to sore penaunce.</L>
<L>&para; Leue not alle men that speke &thorn;e fayre,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at hit ben comyns, burges, or mayre;</L>
<L>In swete wordis &thorn;e nedder was closet,</L>
<L N="208">Disseyuaunt euer and mysloset;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;ou art of adams blode,</L>
<L>With wordis be ware, but &thorn;ou be wode:</L>
<L>A schort worde is comynly sothe</L>
<L N="212">&THORN;at fyrst slydes fro monnes tothe.</L>
<L>&para; Loke ly&yogh;er neuer &thorn;at &thorn;ou be-come,</L>
<L>Kepe &thorn;ys worde for alle and somme.</L>
<L>Law&yogh;e not to of[t] for no solace,</L>
<L N="216">For no kyn myrthe &thorn;at any man mase;</L>
<L>Who lawes alle &thorn;at men may se,</L>
<L>A schrew or a fole hym semes to be.</L>
<L>&para; Thre enmys in &thorn;ys worlde &thorn;er are,</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;at coueyten alle men to for-fare,&mdash;</L>
<L>The deuel, &thorn;e flesshe, &thorn;e worlde also,</L>
<L>That wyrkyn mankynde ful mykyl wo:</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou may strye &thorn;es &thorn;re enmys,</L>
<L N="224">&THORN;ou may be secur of heuen blys.</L>
<L>&para; Also, my chylde, a-gaynes &thorn;y lorde</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou stryfe with no kyn worde,
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="306"></L>
<L>Ne waiour non with hym &thorn;ou lay,</L>
<L N="228">Ne at &thorn;e dyces with hym to play.</L>
<L>&para; Hym that &thorn;ou knawes of gretter state,</L>
<L>Be not hys felaw in rest ne bate.<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou be stad in strange contr&eacute;,</L>
<L N="232">Enserche no fyr &thorn;en falles to the,</L>
<L>Ne take no more to do on honde,</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;ou may hafe menske of alle in londe.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou se any mon fal by strete,</L>
<L N="236">Laweghe not &thorn;er-at in drye ne wete,</L>
<L>But helpe hym vp with alle &thorn;y my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As seynt Ambrose &thorn;e teches ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou that stondys so sure on sete,</L>
<L N="240">Ware lest &thorn;y hede falle to &thorn;y fete.</L>
<L>&para; My chylde, yf &thorn;ou stonde at &thorn;o masse,</L>
<L>At vndur stondis bothe more and lasse,</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;o prest rede not at &thorn;y wylle,</L>
<L N="244">Repreue hym no&yogh;t, but holde &thorn;e stylle.</L>
<L>&para; To any wy&yogh;t &thorn;y counselle yf &thorn;ou schewe,</L>
<L>Be war &thorn;at he be not a schrewe,</L>
<L>Lest he disclaundyr &thorn;e with tong</L>
<L N="248">Amonge alle men, bothe olde and &yogh;ong.</L>
<L>&para; Bekenyng, fynguryng, non &thorn;ou vse,</L>
<L>And pryu&eacute; rownyng loke &thorn;ou refuse.</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou mete kny&yogh;t, &yogh;omon, or knaue,</L>
<L N="252">Haylys hym a-non, "syre, god &yogh;ou saue."</L>
<L>Yf he speke fyrst opon &thorn;e &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>Onsware hym gladly with-outen more.</L>
<L>&para; Go not forthe as a dombe freke,</L>
<L N="256">Syn god hase laft the tonge to speke;</L>
<L>Lest men sey be sibbe or couthe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to relation or friend.</NOTE></L>
<L>"&YOGH;ond is a mon with-outen mouthe."</L>
<L>&para; Speke neuer vnhonestly of woman kynde,</L>
<L N="260">Ne let hit neuer renne in &thorn;y mynde;
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="307"></L>
<L>&THORN;e boke hym calles a chorle of chere,</L>
<L>That vylany spekes be wemen sere:</L>
<L>For alle we ben of wymmen born,</L>
<L N="264">And oure fadurs vs be-forne;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore hit is a vnhonest thyng</L>
<L>To speke of hem in any hethyng.<NOTE PLACE="foot">contempt, scorn. O.N. <I>he&eth;ung</I>, H. Coleridge.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; Also a wyfe be, falle of ry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="268">To worschyp hyr husbonde bothe day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To his byddyng be obediente,</L>
<L>And hym to serue with-outen offence.</L>
<L>&para; Yf two brether be at debate,</L>
<L N="272">Loke no&thorn;er &thorn;ou for&thorn;er in hor hate,</L>
<L>But helpe to staunche hom of malice;</L>
<L>&THORN;en &thorn;ou art frende to bothe I-wys.</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou go with a-no&thorn;er at &thorn;o gate,</L>
<L N="276">And &yogh;e be bothe of on astate,</L>
<L>Be curtasye and let hym haue &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>That is no vylanye, as men me say;</L>
<L>And he be comen of gret kynraden,</L>
<L N="280">Go no be-fore &thorn;awgh &thorn;ou be beden;</L>
<L>And yf &thorn;at he &thorn;y maystur be,</L>
<L>Go not be-fore, for curtas&eacute;,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er in fylde, wode, no&thorn;er launde,</L>
<L N="284">Ne euen hym with, but he commaunde.</L>
<L>&para; Yf &thorn;ou schalle on pilgrimage go,</L>
<L>Be not &thorn;e thryd felaw for wele ne wo;</L>
<L>Thre oxen in plowgh may neuer wel drawe,</L>
<L N="288">No&thorn;er be craft, ry&yogh;t, ne lawe,<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;if &thorn;ou be profert to drynk of cup,</L>
<L>Drynke not al of, ne no way sup;</L>
<L>Drynk menskely and gyf agayne,</L>
<L N="292">&THORN;at is a curtasye, to speke in playne,</L>
<L>&para; In bedde yf &thorn;ou falle herberet to be,</L>
<L>With felawe, maystur, or her degr&eacute;,
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="308"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt enquere be curtasye</L>
<L N="296">In what par[t] of &thorn;e bedde he wylle lye;</L>
<L>Be honest and lye &thorn;ou fer hym fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art not wyse but &thorn;ou do so.</L>
<L>&para; With woso men, bo&thorn;e fer and negh,</L>
<L N="300">The falle to go, loke &thorn;ou be slegh</L>
<L>To aske his nome, and qweche he be,</L>
<L>Whidur he wille: kepe welle &thorn;es thre.</L>
<L>&para; With freres on pilgrimage yf &thorn;at &thorn;ou go,</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;at &thorn;ei wille &yogh;yme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">AS. <I>g&ymacr;man</I>, attend, regard, observe, keep.</NOTE> wilne &thorn;ou also;</L>
<L>Als on ny&yogh;t &thorn;ou take &thorn;y rest,</L>
<L>And byde &thorn;e day as tru mannes gest.</L>
<L>&para; In no kyn house &thorn;at rede mon is,</L>
<L N="308">Ne womon of &thorn;o same colour y-wys,</L>
<L>Take neuer &thorn;y Innes for no kyn nede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ose be folke &thorn;at ar to drede.</L>
<L>&para; Yf any thurgh sturnes &thorn;e oppose,</L>
<L N="312">Onswere hym mekely and make hym glose:</L>
<L>But glosand wordys &thorn;at falsed is,</L>
<L>Forsake, and alle that is omys.</L>
<L>&para; Also yf &thorn;ou haue a lorde,</L>
<L N="316">And stondes by-fore hym at &thorn;e borde,</L>
<L>While &thorn;at &thorn;ou speke, kepe welle &thorn;y honde,</L>
<L>Thy fete also in pece let stonde,</L>
<L>&para; His curtas&eacute; nede he most breke,&mdash;</L>
<L N="320">Stirraunt fyngurs toos when he shalle speke.</L>
<L>Be stabulle of chere and sumwhat ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne ouer alle wayue &thorn;ou not thy sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&para; Gase not on walles with &thorn;y neghe<NOTE PLACE="foot">thine eye</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="324">Fyr ne negh, logh ne heghe;</L>
<L>Let not &thorn;e post be-cum &thorn;y staf,</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;ou be callet a dotet daf;</L>
<L>Ne delf &thorn;ou neuer nose thyrle</L>
<L N="328">With thombe ne fyngur, as &yogh;ong gyrle;
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="309"></L>
<L>&para; Rob not &thorn;y arme ne no&yogh;t hit claw,</L>
<L>Ne bogh not doun &thorn;y hede to law;</L>
<L>Whil any man spekes with grete besenes,</L>
<L N="332">Herken his wordis with-outen distresse.</L>
<L>&para; By strete or way yf &thorn;ou schalle go,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;es two &thorn;ynges &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;e fro,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er to harme chylde ne best,</L>
<L N="336">With castyng, turnyng west ne est;</L>
<L>Ne chaunge &thorn;ou not in face coloure,</L>
<L>For lyghtnes of worde in halle ne boure;</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;y vysage chaunge for no&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="340">Men say &thorn;e 'trespas &thorn;ou hase wro&yogh;ght.'</L>
<L>&para; By-fore &thorn;y lorde, ne mawes &thorn;ou make</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wylle curtasie with &thorn;e take.</L>
<L>With hondes vnwasshen take neuer &thorn;y mete;</L>
<L N="344">Fro alle &thorn;es vices loke &thorn;ou &thorn;e kepe.</L>
<L>&para; Loke &thorn;ou sytt&mdash;and make no stryf&mdash;<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Where &thorn;o est<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>ost</I></NOTE> commaundys, or ellis &thorn;o wyf.</L>
<L>Eschewe &thorn;e he&yogh;est place with wyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">AS. <I>win</I>, contention, labour, war; <I>win, wyn</I>, joy, pleasure.</NOTE></L>
<L N="348">But &thorn;ou be beden to sitt &thorn;er-in.</L>
<L>Of curtasie here endis &thorn;e secunde fyt,</L>
<L>To heuen crist mot oure saules flyt!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="book">
<HEAD>THE THIRD BOOK.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De officiarijs in curijs dominorum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="352">Now speke we wylle of officiers</L>
<L>Of court, and als of hor mestiers.</L>
<L>Foure men &thorn;er ben &thorn;at &yogh;erdis schalle bere,</L>
<L>Porter, marshalle, stuarde, vsshere;</L>
<L>The porter schalle haue &thorn;e lengest wande,</L>
<L N="356">The marshalle a schorter schalle haue in hande;
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="310"></L>
<L>The vssher of chambur smallest schalle haue,</L>
<L>The stuarde in honde schalle haue a stafe,</L>
<L>A fyngur gret, two wharters long,</L>
<L N="360">To reule &thorn;e men of court ymong.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Ianitore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the duties of Prince Edward's Porters, A.D. 1474, in <I>Household Ordinances</I>, p. <SUP>*</SUP>30, and of Henry VIII.'s Porters, <I>ibid.</I> p. 239.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The porter falle to kepe &thorn;o &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>&THORN;e stokkes with hym erly and late;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if any man hase in court mys-gayne,</L>
<L N="364">To porter warde he schalle be tane,</L>
<L>&THORN;er to a-byde &thorn;e lordes wylle,</L>
<L>What he wille deme by ry&yogh;twys skylle.</L>
<L>For wesselle clothes, &thorn;at no&yogh;t be solde,</L>
<L N="368">&THORN;e po[r]ter hase &thorn;at warde in holde.</L>
<L>Of strangers also &thorn;at comen to court,</L>
<L>&THORN;o porter schalle warne ser at a worde.</L>
<L>Lyueray he hase of mete and drynke,</L>
<L N="372">And settis with hym who so hym thynke.</L>
<L>When so euer &thorn;o lorde remewe schalle</L>
<L>To castelle til o&thorn;er as hit may falle,</L>
<L>For cariage &thorn;e porter hors schalle hyre,</L>
<L N="376">Foure pens a pece with-in &thorn;o schyre;</L>
<L>Be statut he schalle take &thorn;at on &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e kyngis crye in faye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Marescallo aule.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Though Edward IV. had Marshals (<I>Household Ordinances</I>, p. 84, &amp;c.), one of whom made the Surnape when the King was in the Hall <MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="page">, or Estate in the Surnape <MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="page">, yet there is no separate heading or allowance for them in the <I>Liber Niger</I>. Two yeomen Ushers are mentioned in p. 38, but the two yeomen Ewars, their two Grooms and Page, p. 84, perform (nearly) the duties given above to the Usher and his Grooms.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now of marschalle of halle wylle I spelle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. spekle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="380">And what falle to hys offyce now wylle y telle;
<PB REF="00000471.tif" N="311"></L>
<L>In absence of stuarde he shalle arest</L>
<L>Who so euer is rebelle in court or fest;</L>
<L>&YOGH;omon-vsshere, and grome also,</L>
<L N="384">Vndur hym ar &thorn;es two:</L>
<L>&THORN;o grome for fuelle &thorn;at schalle brenne</L>
<L>In halle, chambur, to kechyn, as I &thorn;e kenne,</L>
<L>He shalle delyuer hit ilke a dele,</L>
<L N="388">In halle make fyre at yche a mele;</L>
<L>Borde, trestuls, and formes also,</L>
<L>&THORN;e cupborde in his warde schalle go,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dosurs cortines to henge in halle,</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;es offices nede do he schalle;</L>
<L>Bryng in fyre on alhalawgh day,</L>
<L>To condulmas euen, I dar welle say.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Per quantum tempus armigeri habebunt liberatam <I>et</I> ignis ardebit in aula.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So longe squiers lyuer&eacute;s shalle hafe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Edward IV.'s Esquiers for the Body, IIII, had 'for wynter lyverey from All Hallowentide (Nov. 1) tyll Estyr, one percher wax, one candell wax, ij candells Paris, one tallwood and dimid|ium, and wages in the countyng-house.' <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 36. So the Bannerettes, IIII, or Bacheler Knights <MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="page">, who are kervers and cupberers, take 'for wynter season, from Allhallowentyde till Estyr, one tortays, one percher, ii candelles wax, ii candelles Paris, ii talwood, ii faggotts,' and rushes, litter, all the year; which the Esquiers have too. The Percy household allowance of Wax was cciiij score vij lb. dimid. of Wax for th' expensys of my House for oone hole Yere. Viz. Sysez, <I>Pryketts</I>, Quarions, and <I>Torches</I> after ix d. the lb. by estimacion; p. 12.</NOTE></L>
<L N="396">Of grome of halle, or ellis his knafe;</L>
<L>But fyre shalle brenne in halle at mete,</L>
<L>To <I>Cena</I> domini &thorn;at men hase ete;</L>
<L>&THORN;er brow&yogh;t schalle be a holyn kene,<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="400">&THORN;at sett schalle be in erber grene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at schalle be to alhalawgh day,</L>
<L>And of be skyfted, as y &thorn;e say.</L>
<L>In halle marshalle alle men schalle sett</L>
<L N="404">After here degr&eacute;, with-outen lett.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Liber Niger of Edw. IV. assigns this duty to one of the Gentylmen Usshers. <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 37.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000472.tif" N="312">
<HEAD>&para; De pincernario, panetario, <I>et</I> cocis sibi seruientibus.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The botelar, pantrer, and cokes also,</L>
<L>To hym ar seruauntis with-outen mo;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore on his &yogh;erde skore shalle he<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the Office of Butler of Englond, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 73.</NOTE></L>
<L N="408">Alle messys in halle &thorn;at seruet be,</L>
<L>Commaunde to sett bothe brede and ale</L>
<L>To alle men &thorn;at seruet ben in sale;</L>
<L>&para; To gentilmen with wyne I-bake,</L>
<L N="412">Ellis fayles &thorn;o seruice, y vnder-take;</L>
<L>Iche messe at vj<SUP>d</SUP> breue shalle he</L>
<L>At the countyng house with o&thorn;er men&eacute;;</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;o koke wolde say &thorn;at were more,</L>
<L N="416">&THORN;at is &thorn;o cause &thorn;at he hase hit in skore.</L>
<L>&THORN;e panter<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the Office of Panetry, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 70.</NOTE> also yf he wolde stryfe,</L>
<L>For rewarde &thorn;at sett schalle be be-lyue.</L>
<L>When brede faylys at borde aboute,</L>
<L N="420">The marshalle gares sett with-outen doute</L>
<L>More brede, &thorn;at calde is a rewarde,</L>
<L>So shalle hit be preuet be-fore stuarde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De officio pincernarij.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the Office of Butler of Englond, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 73.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Botler shalle sett for yche a messe</L>
<L N="424">A pot, a lofe, with-outen distresse;</L>
<L>Botler, pantrer, felawes ar ay,</L>
<L>Reken hom to-gedur fulle wel y may.</L>
<L>The marshalle shalle herber alle men in fere,</L>
<L N="428">That ben of court of any mestere;</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e lordys chambur, &thorn;o wadrop to,</L>
<L>&THORN;o vssher of chambur schalle tent &thorn;o two.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De hostiario <I>et</I> suis seruientibus.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Gentylmen Usshers of Chaumbre, IIII, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 37. 'This name ussher is a worde of Frenshe,' p. 38.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Speke I wylle A lytulle qwyle</L>
<L N="432">Of vssher of chambur, with-outen gyle.
<PB REF="00000473.tif" N="313"></L>
<L>&THORN;er is gentylmen, &yogh;omon-vssher also,</L>
<L>Two gromes at &thorn;o lest, A page &thorn;er-to,</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Officio garcionum.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 39. 'Yeomen of Chambre, IIII, to make beddes, to bere or hold torches, to sette bourdes, to apparayle all chaumbres, and suche other servyce as the chaumberlayn, or usshers of chambre command or assigne.' Liber Niger Edw. IV. See also <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 40, Office of Warderobe of Beddes, p. 41, Gromes of Chambyr, X; and the elaborate directions for making Henry VII.'s bed, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 121-2.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Gromes palettis shyn fyle and make litere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Hoc stramentum</I>, lyttere, p. 260, col. 2 (the straw with which the bed was formerly made), Wright's Vocabularies.</NOTE></L>
<L N="436">ix fote on lengthe with-out diswere;</L>
<L>vij fote y-wys hit shalle be brode,</L>
<L>Wele watered, I-wrythen, be craft y-trode,</L>
<L>Wyspes drawen out at fete and syde,</L>
<L N="440">Wele wrethyn and turnyd a-&yogh;ayne &thorn;at tyde;</L>
<L>On legh vnsonken hit shalle be made,</L>
<L>To &thorn;o gurdylstode hegh on lengthe and brade.</L>
<L>For lordys two beddys schalle be made,</L>
<L N="444">Bothe vtter and inner, so god me glade,</L>
<L>&THORN;at henget shalle be with hole sylour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sylure, of valle, or a nother thynge (sylure of a walle), <I>Cela|tura, Celamen</I>, Catholicon, in P. Parv. Fr. <I>Ciel</I>, Heauen, pl. <I>Ciels</I>, a canopie for, and, the Testerne and Valances of a Bed. Cotgrave. A tester over the beadde, <I>canopus</I>. Withals.</NOTE></L>
<L>With crochettis<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Crochet</I>, a small hooke.</NOTE> and loupys sett on lyour;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Lyowre, to bynde wythe precyows clothys. <I>Ligatorium</I>. P. Parv.</NOTE></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o valance on fylour<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fylowre, of barbours crafte, <I>Acutecula, filarium</I>. P. Parv. See note 3, p. 160.</NOTE> shalle henge with wyn,</L>
<L N="448">iij curteyns stre&yogh;t drawen with-inne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at reche schalle euen to grounde a-boute,</L>
<L>No&thorn;er more, no&thorn;er lesse, with-outen doute;</L>
<L>He strykes hom vp with forket wande,</L>
<L N="452">And lappes vp fast a-boute &thorn;e lyft hande;
<PB REF="00000474.tif" N="314"></L>
<L>&THORN;o knop vp turnes, and closes on ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&para; As bolde by nek &thorn;at henges fulle ly&yogh;t.<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;o counturpynt he lays on beddys fete,</L>
<L N="456">Qwysshenes on sydes shyn lye fulle mete.</L>
<L>Tapetis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tapet, a clothe, <I>tappis</I>. Palsgrave, 1530. <I>Tapis</I>, Tapistrie, hangings, &amp;c., of Arras. Cotgrave, 1611. <I>Tapis</I>, carpet, a green square-plot. Miegc, 1684. The hangynges of a house or chambre, in plurali, <I>aul&aelig;a . . Circundo cubiculum aul&aelig;is</I>, to hange the chambre. The carpettes, <I>tapetes</I>. Withals.</NOTE> of spayne on flore by syde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sprad shyn be for pompe and pryde;</L>
<L>&THORN;o chambur sydes ry&yogh;t to &thorn;o dore,</L>
<L N="460">He henges with tapetis &thorn;at ben fulle store;</L>
<L>And fuel to chymn&eacute; hym falle to gete,</L>
<L>And screnes in clof to y-saue &thorn;o hete.</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;o lorde at mete when he is sett,</L>
<L N="464">Borde, trestuls, and fourmes, with-outen let;</L>
<L>&para; Alle thes &thorn;ynges kepe schalle he,</L>
<L>And water in chafer for laydyes fre;</L>
<L>iij perchers of wax &thorn;en shalle he fet,</L>
<L N="468">A-boue &thorn;o chymn&eacute; &thorn;at be sett,</L>
<L>In syce<NOTE PLACE="foot">And he (a Grome of Chambyr) setteth nyghtly, after the seasons of the yere, torchys, tortays, candylles of wax, mortars; and he setteth up the <I>sises</I> in the King's chambre, <I>H. Ord</I>. p. 41, 'these torches, five, seven, or nine; and as many <I>sises</I> sett upp as there bee torches,' <I>ib</I>. p. 114; and dayly iiii other of these gromes, called wayters, to make fyres, to sett up tressyls and bourdes, with yomen of chambre, and to help dresse the beddes of sylke and arras. <I>H. Ord</I>. p. 41.</NOTE> ichon from o&thorn;er shalle be</L>
<L>&THORN;e lenghthe of o&thorn;er &thorn;at men may se,</L>
<L>To brenne, to voide, &thorn;at dronkyn is,</L>
<L N="472">O&thorn;er ellis I wote he dose Amys.</L>
<L>&THORN;o vssher alle-way shalle sitt at dore</L>
<L>At mete, and walke schalle on &thorn;e flore,</L>
<L>To se &thorn;at alle be seruet on ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="476">&THORN;at is his office be day and ny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And byd set borde when tyme schalle be,</L>
<L>And take hom vp when tyme ses he.
<PB REF="00000475.tif" N="315"></L>
<L>&para; The wardrop<NOTE PLACE="foot">Wardroppe, or closet&mdash;garderobe. Palsgrave.</NOTE> he herbers and eke of chambur</L>
<L N="480">Ladyes with bedys of coralle and lambur,</L>
<L>&THORN;o vsshere schalle bydde &thorn;o wardropere</L>
<L>Make redy for alle ny&yogh;t be-fore &thorn;e fere;</L>
<L>&THORN;en bryngis he forthe ny&yogh;t goun also,</L>
<L N="484">And spredys a tapet and qwysshens two,</L>
<L>He layes hom &thorn;en opon a fourme,</L>
<L>And foteshete &thorn;er-on and hit returne.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o lorde schalle skyft hys gown at ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="488">Syttand on foteshete tyl he be dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&THORN;en vssher gose to &thorn;o botr&eacute;,</L>
<L>"Haue in for alle ny&yogh;t, syr," says he;</L>
<L>Fyrst to &thorn;e chaundeler he schalle go,</L>
<L N="492">To take a tortes ly&yogh;t hym fro;</L>
<L>&para; Bothe wyne and ale he tase indede,</L>
<L>&THORN;o botler says, with-outen drede,</L>
<L>No mete for mon schalle sayed<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the duties of Edward IV.'s Sewar, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 36.</NOTE> be,</L>
<L N="496">Bot for kynge or prynce or duke so fre;</L>
<L>For heiers of paraunce also y-wys,</L>
<L>Mete shalle be sayed, now thenkys on this.</L>
<L>&THORN;en to pantr&eacute; he hy&yogh;es be-lyue,</L>
<L N="500">&para; "Syrs, haue in with-outen stryffe;"</L>
<L>Manchet and chet<NOTE PLACE="foot">Manchet was the fine bread; chet, the course. Fr. <I>pain rouffet</I>, Cheat, or boulted bread; houshold bread made of Wheat and Rie mingled. Cotgrave.</NOTE> bred he shalle take,</L>
<L>&THORN;o pantere assayes &thorn;at hit be bake;</L>
<L>A morter of wax &yogh;et wille he bryng,</L>
<L N="504">Fro chambur, syr, with-out lesyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle ny&yogh;t brennes in bassyn clere,</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;o chambur on ny&yogh;t for fyre.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;en &yogh;omon of chambur shynne voyde with ryme,</L>
<L N="508">The torches han holden wele &thorn;at tyme;</L>
<L>Tho chambur dore stekes &thorn;o vssher thenne,</L>
<L>With preket and tortes &thorn;at conne brenne;
<PB REF="00000476.tif" N="316"></L>
<L>Fro cupborde he brynges bothe brede and wyne,</L>
<L N="512">And fyrst assayes hit wele a[nd] fyne.</L>
<L>But fyrst &thorn;e lorde shalle vasshe I-wys,<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fro &thorn;o fyr hous when he comen is;</L>
<L>&THORN;en kneles &thorn;e vssher and gyfes hym drynke,</L>
<L N="516">Brynges hym in bed where he shalle wynke;</L>
<L>In strong styd on palet he lay,</L>
<L>At home tase lefe and gose his way;</L>
<L>&YOGH;omon vssher be-fore &thorn;e dore,</L>
<L N="520">In vttur chambur lies on &thorn;e flore.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De seneschallo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the 'Styward of Housholde,' <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 55-6: 'He is head officer.'</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now speke I wylle of &thorn;o stuarde als,</L>
<L>Few ar trew, but fele ar<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>and</I></NOTE> fals.</L>
<L>&THORN;o clerke of kechyn, countrollour,</L>
<L N="524">Stuarde, coke, and surueyour,</L>
<L>Assenten in counselle, with-outen skorne,</L>
<L>How &thorn;o lorde schalle fare at mete &thorn;o morne.</L>
<L>Yf any deyntethe in countr&eacute; be,</L>
<L N="528">&THORN;o stuarde schewes hit to &thorn;o lorde so fre,</L>
<L>And gares by hyt for any cost,</L>
<L>Hit were grete syn and hit were lost.</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e cours &thorn;o stuarde comes &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="532">&THORN;e seruer hit next of alle kyn men</L>
<L>Mays way and stondes by syde,</L>
<L>Tyl alle be serued at &thorn;at tyde.</L>
<L>At countyng stuarde schalle ben,</L>
<L N="536">Tylle alle be breuet of wax so grene,</L>
<L>Wrytten in-to bokes, with-out let,</L>
<L>&THORN;at be-fore in tabuls hase ben sett,</L>
<L>Tyl countes also &thorn;er-on ben cast,</L>
<L N="540">And somet vp holy at &thorn;o last.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000477.tif" N="317">
<HEAD>&para; De contrarotulatore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the "Countroller of this houshold royall,' <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 58-9.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The Countrollour shalle wryte to hym,</L>
<L>Taunt resceu, no more I myn;</L>
<L>And taunt dispendu &thorn;at same day,</L>
<L N="544">Vncountabulle he is, as y &yogh;ou say.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De superuisore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the duties and allowances of A Surveyour for the Kyng, in <I>Household Ordinances</I>, p. 37.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Surueour and stuarde also,</L>
<L>Thes thre folke and no mo,</L>
<L>For no&yogh;t resayuen bot euer sene</L>
<L N="548">&THORN;at no&thorn;yng fayle and alle be whene;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;o clerke of kechyn schulde not mys,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore &thorn;o countrollour, as hafe I blys,</L>
<L>Wrytes vp &thorn;o somme as euery day,</L>
<L N="552">And helpes to count, as I &yogh;ou say.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Clerico coquine.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the 'chyef clerke of kychyn,' t. Edw. IV., <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 70; and Henry VIII.'s Clerke of the Kitchen, A.D. 1539, <I>ib.</I> p. 235.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The clerke of &thorn;e cochyn shalle alle &thorn;yng breue,</L>
<L>Of men of court, bothe lothe and leue,</L>
<L>Of achatis and dispenses &thorn;en wrytes he,</L>
<L N="556">And wages for gromes and &yogh;emen fre;</L>
<L>At dressour also he shalle stonde,</L>
<L>And fett forthe mete dresset with honde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e spicery and store with hym shalle dwelle,</L>
<L N="560">And mony thynges als, as I no&yogh;t telle,</L>
<L>For clethyng of officers alle in fere,</L>
<L>Saue &thorn;e lorde hym self and ladys dere.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De cancellario.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The duties of the Chauncellor of Englond are not stated in Edw. IV.'s Liber Niger, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 29; but one of the two Clerkys of Grene-Clothe was accustomed to 'delyver the clothinge of hous|holde,' p. 61.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The chaunceler answeres for hor clothyng,</L>
<L N="564">For &yogh;omen, faukeners, and hor horsyng,
<PB REF="00000478.tif" N="318"></L>
<L>For his wardrop and wages also;</L>
<L>And asseles patentis mony and mo;<MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Yf &thorn;o lorde gyf o&yogh;t to terme of lyf,</L>
<L N="568">The chaunceler hit seles with-outen stryf;</L>
<L><I>Tan come nos plerra</I> men seyne, &thorn;er is quando nobis <I>placet</I>,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is, whille vs lykes hym no&yogh;t omys;</L>
<L>Ouer-se hys londes &thorn;at alle be ry&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="572">On of &thorn;o grete he is of my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De thesaurizario.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the 'Thesaurere of Housholde' in Edw. IV.'s Liber Niger, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 56-8: 'the grete charge of polycy and husbandry of all this houshold growyth and stondyth moste part by hys sad and dylygent pourveyaunce and conduytes.'</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now speke y wylle of tresurere,</L>
<L>Husbonde and houswyf he is in fere;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e resayuer he shalle resayue,</L>
<L N="576">Alle &thorn;at is gedurt of bayl&eacute; and grayue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">AS. <I>gerefa</I>, reeve, steward, bailiff.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of &thorn;e lordes courtes and forfetis als,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er &thorn;ay ben ry&yogh;t or &thorn;ay ben fals.</L>
<L>To &thorn;o clerke of cochen he payes mon&eacute;</L>
<L N="580">For vetayle to bye opon &thorn;o countr&eacute;:</L>
<L>The clerke to kater and pulter is,</L>
<L>To baker and butler bothe y-wys</L>
<L>Gyffys seluer to bye in alle thyng</L>
<L N="584">&THORN;at longes to here office, with-outen lesyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tresurer schalle gyfe alkyn wage,</L>
<L>To squyer, &yogh;omon, grome, or page.</L>
<L>&THORN;o resayuer and &thorn;o tresurer,</L>
<L N="588">&THORN;o clerke of cochyn and chaunceler,</L>
<L>Grayuis, and baylys, and parker,</L>
<L>Schone come to acountes euery &yogh;ere</L>
<L>By-fore &thorn;o auditour of &thorn;o lorde onone,</L>
<L N="592">&THORN;at schulde be trew as any stone;</L>
<L>Yf he dose hom no ry&yogh;t lele,</L>
<L>To A baron of chekker &thorn;ay mun hit pele.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000479.tif" N="319">
<HEAD>&para; De receptore firmarum.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of &thorn;e resayuer speke wylle I,</L>
<L N="596">&THORN;at fermys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rents, in kind or money; AS. <I>feorme</I>, food, goods.</NOTE> resayuys wytturly</L>
<L>Of grayuys, and hom aquetons makes,</L>
<L>Sex pons &thorn;er-fore to feys he takes,</L>
<L>And pays feys to parkers als I-wys,</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;er-of at acountes he loued<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> loned.</NOTE> is,</L>
<L>And ouer-seys castels, maners a-boute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no&yogh;t falle with-in ne with-oute.</L>
<L>Now let we &thorn;es officers be,</L>
<L N="604">And telle we wylle of smaller men&eacute;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Auenario.<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Avener of Edw. IV. is mentioned in <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 69. See the Charge of Henry VIII.'s Stable, A.D. 1526, <I>ib.</I> p. 206-7.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e Aueyner schalle ordeyn prouande<NOTE PLACE="foot">Prouender or menglid corne&mdash;fovrraige..<I>provende</I>. Palsgrave.</NOTE> good won,</L>
<L>For &thorn;o lordys horsis euerychon;</L>
<L>&THORN;ay schyn haue two cast<NOTE PLACE="foot">See 'two <I>cast</I> of brede,' l. 631. 'One caste of brede' for the Steward's yeoman, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 56, &amp;c.</NOTE> of hay,</L>
<L N="608">A pek of prouande on a day;</L>
<L>Euery horse schalle so muche haue,</L>
<L>At racke and manger &thorn;at standes with staue.</L>
<L>A maystur of horsys a squyer<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mayster of the horses&mdash;<I>escvier de escvirie.</I> Palsg.</NOTE> &thorn;er is,</L>
<L N="612">Aueyner and ferour vndur hym I-wys;</L>
<L>&THORN;ose &yogh;omen &thorn;at olde sadels schyn haue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schyn be last for kny&yogh;t and knaue,</L>
<L>For yche a hors &thorn;at ferroure<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Rogers's <I>Agriculture and Prices in England</I>, v. 1, p. 280-1. The latest prices he gives for shoeing are in 1400; "Alton Barnes, Shoeing 5 horses, a year, 6s. 8d. Takley, Shoeing 2 cart horses [a year] 1s. 8d." A.D. 1466, 'fore shoyinge ij.d.' <I>Manners and Household Expenses</I> (ed. Dawson Turner), 1841, p. 380. (Sir Jn. Howard, Knt., 1462-9.) The Percy allowance in 1512 was "ij s. viiij d. every Hors Shoynge for the hole Yere by estimacion, Viz. a Hors to be shodd oons in iij moneths withowt they jornay." p. 24. A horse's daily allowance was 'a Peck of Oats, or 4d. in Breade after iiij Loiffes, 4d. for Provaunder, from 29th Septr. 8 Hen. VIII. to 3rd May following,' p. 266.</NOTE> schalle scho,</L>
<L N="616">An halpeny on day he takes hym to;
<PB REF="00000480.tif" N="320"></L>
<L>Vndur ben gromes and pages mony one,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben at wage euerychone;</L>
<L>Som at two pons on a day,</L>
<L N="620">And som at iij ob., I &yogh;ou say;<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Mony of hem fote-men &thorn;er ben,</L>
<L>&THORN;at rennen by &thorn;e brydels of ladys shene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De pistore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See Edw. IV.'s Office of Bakehouse, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 68-70. 'The sergeaunt of thys office to make continually of every busshell, halfe chiete halfe rounde, besydes the flowre for the Kinges mouthe, xxvii loves, every one weying, after one daye olde, xxiii ounces of troye weyghtes.' p. 69.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of &thorn;o baker now speke y wylle,</L>
<L N="624">And wat longes his office vntylle;</L>
<L>Of a lunden buschelle he shalle bake</L>
<L>xx louys, I vndur-take;</L>
<L>Manchet and chet to make brom<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Read</I> broun, brown.</NOTE> bred hard,</L>
<L N="628">For chaundeler and grehoundes and huntes reward.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De venatore <I>et</I> suis canibus.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A halpeny &thorn;o hunte takes on &thorn;e day</L>
<L>For euery hounde, &thorn;o sothe to say:</L>
<L>&THORN;o vewter, two cast of brede he tase,</L>
<L N="632">Two lesshe of grehoundes yf &thorn;at he hase;</L>
<L>To yche a bone, &thorn;at is to telle,</L>
<L>If I to &yogh;ou &thorn;e sothe shalle spelle;</L>
<L>By-syde hys vantage &thorn;at may be-falle,</L>
<L N="636">Of skynnes and o&thorn;er thynges with-alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hunteres con telle better &thorn;an I,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore I leue hit wytt[ur]ly.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000481.tif" N="321">
<HEAD>&para; De aquario.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In Edward the Fourth's Court, 'Knyghts of Household, XII, bachelers sufficiant, and most valient men of that ordre of every countrey' had 'to serve the King of his bason.' <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 33.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And speke I wylle of o&thorn;er mystere</L>
<L N="640">&THORN;at falles to court, as &yogh;e mun here;</L>
<L>An euwere in halle &thorn;ere nedys to be,</L>
<L>And chandelew schalle haue and alle napere;</L>
<L>He schalle gef water to gentilmen,</L>
<L N="644">And als in alle &yogh;omen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; Qui debent manus lauare <I>et</I> in quorum domibus.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In kynges court and dukes also,</L>
<L>&THORN;er &yogh;omen schynne wasshe and no mo;&mdash;</L>
<L>In duke Ionys house a &yogh;oman &thorn;er was,</L>
<L N="648">For his rewarde prayde suche a grace;</L>
<L>&THORN;e duke gete graunt &thorn;er-of in londe,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e kyng his fader, I vndudurstonde.&mdash;(<I>so</I>)</L>
<L>Wosoeuer gefes water in lordys chaunber,</L>
<L N="652">In presens of lorde or leued&eacute; dere,</L>
<L>He schalle knele downe opon his kne,</L>
<L>Ellys he for&yogh;etes his curtas&eacute;;</L>
<L>&THORN;is euwer schalle hele his lordes borde,</L>
<L N="656">With dowbulle napere at on bare worde:</L>
<L>The seluage to &thorn;o lordes syde with-inne,</L>
<L>And doun schalle heng &thorn;at o&thorn;er may wynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ouer nape schalle dowbulle be layde,</L>
<L N="660">To &thorn;o vttur syde &thorn;e seluage brade;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ouer seluage he schalle replye,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Replier</I>, To redouble, to bow, fould, or plait into many doublings. Cotgrave.</NOTE></L>
<L>As towelle hit were fayrest in hye;</L>
<L>Browers<NOTE PLACE="foot">Napkins? O. Fr. <I>brueroi</I> is <I>bruy&egrave;re</I>, heath.</NOTE> he schalle cast &thorn;er-opon,</L>
<L N="664">&THORN;at &thorn;e lorde schulle clense his fyngers [on],</L>
<L>&THORN;e leuedy and whoseuer syttes with-inne,</L>
<L>Alle browers schynne haue bothe more and myn.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000482.tif" N="322">
<HEAD>&para; De panetario.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;enne comes &thorn;e pantere with loues thre,</L>
<L N="668">&THORN;at square are coruyn of trenchour fre,</L>
<L>To sett with-inne and oon with-oute,</L>
<L>And saller y-coueryd and sett in route;</L>
<L>With &thorn;o ouemast lofe hit shalle be sett,<MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="672">With-oute forthe square, with-outen lett;</L>
<L>Two keruyng knyfes with-oute one,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thrydde to &thorn;o lorde, and als a spone.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Cultellis domini.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of &thorn;o two &thorn;o haftes schynne outwarde be,</L>
<L N="676">Of &thorn;e thrydd &thorn;e hafte inwarde lays he,</L>
<L>&THORN;e spony stele &thorn;er by schalle be layde;</L>
<L>Moo loues of trenchirres at a brayde</L>
<L>He settes, and seruys euyr in fere</L>
<L N="680">To duches his wyne &thorn;at is so dere.</L>
<L>Two loues of trenchors and salt &thorn;o,</L>
<L>He settes be-fore his son also;</L>
<L>A lofe of trenchours and salt on last,</L>
<L N="684">At bordes ende he settes in hast.</L>
<L>&THORN;en brede he brynges, in towelle wrythyn,</L>
<L>Thre lofys of &thorn;o wyte schalle be geuyn;</L>
<L>A chet lofe to &thorn;o elmys dyshe,</L>
<L N="688">We&thorn;er he seruyd be with flesshe or fysche;</L>
<L>At a&thorn;er ende he castes a cope,</L>
<L>Layde down on borde, &thorn;e endys plyed vp.</L>
<L>That he assayes knelande on kne,</L>
<L N="692">&THORN;o keruer hym parys a schyuer so fre;</L>
<L>And touches &thorn;o louys yn quere a-boute,</L>
<L>&THORN;o pantere hit etys with-oute dowte;</L>
<L>&THORN;o euwere thurgh towelle syles<NOTE PLACE="foot">? Du. <I>zijgen</I> (<I>door een zifte ofte Stramijn</I>), to runne (through a Sift or a Strainer.). <I>een Suyle</I> a Pale or a Water-pale. Hexham.</NOTE> clene,</L>
<L N="696">His water into &thorn;o bassynges shene;</L>
<L>&THORN;o ouer bassyn &thorn;er-on schalle close,</L>
<L>A towelle &thorn;er-on, as I suppose,
<PB REF="00000483.tif" N="323"></L>
<L>&THORN;at folden schalle be with fulle grete lore,</L>
<L N="700">Two quarters on lenkethe and sumdele more;</L>
<L>A qwyte cuppe of tre &thorn;er-by shalle be,</L>
<L>&THORN;er-with &thorn;o water assay schalle he;</L>
<L>Quelmes<NOTE PLACE="foot">covers. 'Ovyr quelmyd or ouer hyllyde. <I>Obvolutus.</I>' P. Parv.</NOTE> hit agayn by-fore alle men;</L>
<L N="704">&THORN;o keruer &thorn;e bassynges tase vp &thorn;enne;</L>
<L>Annaunciande squier, or ellis a kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;o towelle down tase by fulle good ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;o cuppe he tase in honde also,</L>
<L N="708">&THORN;o keruer powres wat[er] &thorn;e cuppe into;</L>
<L>The kny&yogh;t to &thorn;o keruer haldes anon,</L>
<L>He says hit ar he more schalle don;</L>
<L>&THORN;o cuppe &thorn;en voyde is in &thorn;o flette,<NOTE PLACE="foot">A. S. <I>flett</I>, room, hall.</NOTE></L>
<L N="712">&THORN;e euwer hit takes with-outen lette.</L>
<L>The towelle two kny&yogh;htis schyn halde in fere,</L>
<L>Be-fore &thorn;e lordes sleues, &thorn;at ben so dere;</L>
<L>The ouer bassyn &thorn;ay halde neuer &thorn;e queder,</L>
<L N="716">Quylle &thorn;o keruer powre water in-to &thorn;e nedur.</L>
<L>For a pype &thorn;er is insyde so clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at water deuoydes, of seluer schene;</L>
<L>&THORN;en settes he &thorn;e nethyr, I vnd[u]rstonde,</L>
<L N="720">In &thorn;e ouer, and voydes with bothe is honde;</L>
<L>And brynges to &thorn;e euwer &thorn;er he come fro;</L>
<L>To &thorn;o lordys bordes a&yogh;ayn con go;</L>
<L>And layes iiij trenchours &thorn;o lorde be-fore,</L>
<L N="724">&THORN;e fyft aboue by good lore;</L>
<L>By hym self thre schalle he dresse,</L>
<L>To cut opon &thorn;e lordes messe;<MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Smale towelle a-boute his necke shalle bene,</L>
<L N="728">To clens his knyfys &thorn;at ben so kene.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De Elemosinario.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See The Almonry of Henry VIII. A.D. 1526, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 154, and p. 144; A.D. 1539, <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 239.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; The aumenere by &thorn;is hathe sayde grace,</L>
<L>And &thorn;o almes dysshe hase sett in place;
<PB REF="00000484.tif" N="324"></L>
<L>&THORN;er-in &thorn;e keruer a lofe schalle sette,</L>
<L N="732">To serue god fyrst with-outen lette;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese o&thorn;er lofes he parys a-boute,</L>
<L>Lays hit myd dysshe with-outen doute.</L>
<L>&THORN;e smalle lofe he cuttis euen in twynne,</L>
<L N="736">&THORN;o ouer dole in two lays to hym.</L>
<L>The aumenere a rod schalle haue in honde,</L>
<L>As office for almes, y vndurstonde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e broken met he kepys y wate,</L>
<L N="740">To dele to pore men at &thorn;e &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>And drynke &thorn;at leues serued in halle;</L>
<L>Of ryche and pore bothe grete and smalle.</L>
<L>He is sworne to ouer-se &thorn;e seruis wele,</L>
<L N="744">And dele hit to &thorn;e pore euery dele;</L>
<L>Seluer he deles rydand by way;</L>
<L>And his almys dysshe, as I &yogh;ou say,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e porest man &thorn;at he can fynde,</L>
<L N="748">O&thorn;er ellys I wot he is vnkynde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De ferculario.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; This wyle &thorn;o squyer to kechyn shalle go,</L>
<L>And brynges a bof for assay &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&THORN;o Coke assayes &thorn;e mete vngry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="752">&THORN;o sewer he takes and kouers on ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Wo so euer he takes &thorn;at mete to bere,</L>
<L>Schalle not so hardy &thorn;o couertoure rere,</L>
<L>For colde ne hote, I warne &yogh;ou alle,</L>
<L N="756">For suspecyon of tresoun as may befalle.</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;o syluer dysshe wylle algate brenne,</L>
<L>A sotelt&eacute; I wylle &thorn;e kenne,</L>
<L>Take &thorn;e bredde coruyn and lay by-twene,</L>
<L N="760">And kepe &thorn;e welle hit be not sene;</L>
<L>&para; I teche hit for no curtayse,</L>
<L>But for &thorn;yn ese.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e sewer comys vnto &thorn;e borde,</L>
<L N="764">Alle &thorn;e mete he sayes at on bare worde,
<PB REF="00000485.tif" N="325"></L>
<L>&THORN;e potage fyrst with brede y-coruyn,</L>
<L>Couerys hom agayn lest &thorn;ey ben storuyn;</L>
<L>With fysshe or flessh yf [they] be serued,</L>
<L N="768">A morselle &thorn;er-of shalle he be keruyd;</L>
<L>And touche &thorn;e messe ouer alle aboute,</L>
<L>&THORN;o sewer hit etis with-outen doute.</L>
<L>With baken mete yf he seruyd be &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="772">&THORN;o lydes vp-rered or he fyr go,</L>
<L>&THORN;e past or pye he sayes with-inne,</L>
<L>Dippes bredde in grau&eacute; no more ne mynne;</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;e baken mete be colde, as may byfalle,</L>
<L N="776">A gobet of &thorn;o self he sayes with-alle.</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou &thorn;at berys mete in hande,</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;o sewer stonde, loke &thorn;ou stande;</L>
<L>Yf he knele, knele &thorn;ou so longe for o&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="780">&para; Tylle mete be sayde &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase broght.<MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As oft at hegh borde yf brede be nede,</L>
<L>The butler two louys takys indede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at on settes down, &thorn;at o&thorn;er agayn</L>
<L N="784">He barys to cupborde in towelle playn.</L>
<L>As oft as &thorn;e keruer fettys drynke,</L>
<L>&THORN;e butler assayes hit how good hym thynke;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e lordys cupp &thorn;at leuys vndrynken,</L>
<L N="788">Into &thorn;e almesdisshe hit schalle be sonken.</L>
<L>The keruer anon with-outen thou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Vnkouers &thorn;e cup &thorn;at he hase brou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e couertoure wyn he powres owt,</L>
<L N="792">Or in-to a spare pece, with-outen doute;</L>
<L>Assayes, an gefes &thorn;o lorde to drynke,</L>
<L>Or settes hit doun as hym goode thynke.</L>
<L>&THORN;o keruer<NOTE PLACE="foot">Edward IV. had 'Bannerettes, IIII, or Bacheler Knights, to be kervers and cupberers in his Courte.' 'The kerver at the boarde, after the King is passed it, may chese for hymself one dyshe or two, that plentie is among. . . Theis kervers and cupberers. . them nedeth to be well spede in teking of degree in <I>the schole of urbanytie.' H. Ord.</I> p. 32-3.</NOTE> schalle kerue &thorn;o lordes mete,
<PB REF="00000486.tif" N="326"></L>
<L N="796">Of what kyn pece &thorn;at he wylle ete;</L>
<L>And on hys trenchour he hit layes,</L>
<L>On &thorn;ys maner with-out displayes;</L>
<L>In almesdysshe he layes yche dele,</L>
<L N="800">&THORN;at he is with serued at &thorn;o mele;</L>
<L>But he sende hit to ony strongere,</L>
<L>A pese &thorn;at is hym leue and dere,</L>
<L>And send hys potage also,</L>
<L N="804">&THORN;at schalle not to &thorn;e almes go.</L>
<L>Of keruer more, yf I shulde telle,</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er fytt &thorn;enne most I spelle,</L>
<L>Ther-fore I let hit here ouer passe,</L>
<L N="808">To make oure talkyng summedelasse.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e lorde hase eten, &thorn;o sewer schalle bryng</L>
<L>&THORN;o surnape on his schulder bryng,</L>
<L>A narew towelle, a brode be-syde,</L>
<L N="812">And of hys hondes he lettes hit slyde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e vssher ledes &thorn;at on hed ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;o aumener &thorn;o o&thorn;er away shalle dy&yogh;t.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e vssher comys to &thorn;e borde ende,</L>
<L N="816">&THORN;o narow towelle he strecches vnkende;</L>
<L>Be-fore &thorn;o lorde and &thorn;e lady so dere,</L>
<L>Dowbelle he playes &thorn;o towelle &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Whenne &thorn;ay haue wasshen and grace is sayde,</L>
<L N="820">Away he takes at a brayde;</L>
<L>Awoydes &thorn;o borde in-to &thorn;o flore,</L>
<L>Tase away &thorn;o trestis &thorn;at ben so store.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>&para; De candelario.<NOTE PLACE="foot">See the 'Office of Chaundlerye,' <I>H. Ord.</I> p. 82-3. Paris candles, torches, morters, tortayes, sizes, and smalle lightes, are mentioned there.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now speke I wylle a lytulle whyle</L>
<L N="824">Of &thorn;o chandeler, with-outen gyle,
<PB REF="00000487.tif" N="327"></L>
<L>&THORN;at torches<NOTE PLACE="foot">Torche. <I>Cereus.</I> P. Parv.</NOTE> and tortes<NOTE PLACE="foot">? same as <I>tortayes,</I> p. 314, note<SUP>2</SUP>; p. 326, <I>n.</I></NOTE> and preketes<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pryket, of a candylstykke, or other lyke. <I>Stiga</I>, P. Parv. Candlesticks (says Mr Way) in ancient times were not fashioned with nozzles, but with long spikes or <I>prykets</I>... (See wood cut at the end of this book.) In the Memoriale of Henry, prior of Canterbury, A.D. 1285, the term <I>prikett</I> denotes, not the candlestick, but the candle, formed with a corresponding cavity at one end, whereby it was securely fixed upon the spike. p. 413, n. 1. Henry VIII.'s allowance 'unto our right dere and welbilovede the Lady Lucy,' July 16, 1533, included 'at our Chaundrye barr, in Wynter, every night oon <I>preket</I> and foure syses of Waxe, with eight Candells white lights, and oon Torche.' <I>Orig. Letters</I>, ed. Ellis, Series I., vol. ii. p. 31.</NOTE> con make,</L>
<L>Perchours,<NOTE PLACE="foot">See note<NOTE PLACE="foot">Torche. <I>Cereus.</I> P. Parv.</NOTE>, p. 311.</NOTE> smale condel, I vnder-take;</L>
<L>Of wax &thorn;ese candels alle &thorn;at brennen,</L>
<L N="828">And morter of wax &thorn;at I wele kenne;</L>
<L>&THORN;o snof of hom dose a-way</L>
<L>With close sesours, as I &yogh;ow say;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sesours ben schort and rownde y-close,</L>
<L N="832">With plate of irne vp-on bose.</L>
<L>In chambur no ly&yogh;t &thorn;er shalle be brent,</L>
<L>Bot of wax &thorn;er-to, yf &yogh;e take tent;</L>
<L>In halle at soper schalle caldels (<I>so</I>) brenne<MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="836">Of parys, &thorn;er-in &thorn;at alle men kenne;</L>
<L>Iche messe a candelle fro alhalawghe day</L>
<L>To candelmesse, as I &yogh;ou say;</L>
<L>Of candel liueray squiyers schalle haue,</L>
<L N="840">So long, if hit is mon wille kraue.</L>
<L>Of brede and ale also &thorn;o boteler</L>
<L>Schalle make lyuer&eacute; thurgh-out &thorn;e &yogh;ere</L>
<L>To squyers, and also wyn to kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="844">Or ellys he dose not his office ry&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Here endys the thryd speche.</L>
<L>Of alle oure synnes cryst be oure leche,</L>
<L>And bryng vs to his vonyng place!</L>
<L N="848">Amen, sayes &yogh;e, for hys grete grace!</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Amen, par charite.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
