<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000558.tif" N="398">

<PB REF="00000559.tif" N="399">
<HEAD>Symon's Lesson of Wysedome for all Maner Chyldryn.[<I>From MS. Bodl.</I> 832, <I>leaf</I> 174.]</HEAD> 
<HEADNOTE><P>[The Rev. J. R. Lumby has kindly sent me the following amusing 'lesson of wysedome' to 'all maner chyldryn', signed Symon, which he found in the Bodleian. Mr G. Parker has read the proof with the MS. Lydgate sinned against most of its precepts. It makes the rod the great persuader to learning and gentleness.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>All maner chyldryn, ye lysten &amp; lere</L>
<L>A lesson of wysedome &thorn;at ys wryte here!</L>
<L>My chyld, y rede &thorn;e be wys, and take hede of &thorn;is ryme!</L>
<L N="4">Old men yn prouerbe sayde by old tyme</L>
<L>'A chyld were beter to be vnbore</L>
<L>Than to be vntaught, and so be lore.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare "Better vnfedde then vntaughte" in <I>Seager's Schoole of Vertue,</I> above, p. 348, l. 725.</NOTE></L>
<L>The chyld &thorn;at hath hys wyll alway</L>
<L N="8">Shal thryve late, y thei<NOTE PLACE="foot">thee</NOTE> wel say,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-for euery gode mannys chyld</L>
<L>That is to wanton and to wyld,</L>
<L>Lerne wel this lesson for sertayn,</L>
<L N="12">That thou may be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> beter man.</L>
<L>Chyld, y warne &thorn;ee yn al wyse</L>
<L>That &thorn;u tel trowth &amp; make no lyes.</L>
<L>Chyld, be not froward, be not prowde,</L>
<L N="16">But hold vp &thorn;y hedde &amp; speke a-lowde;</L>
<L>And when eny man spekyth to the,</L>
<L>Do of &thorn;y hode and bow thy kne,</L>
<L>And waysch thy handes &amp; &thorn;y face,</L>
<L N="20">And be curteys yn euery place.
<PB REF="00000560.tif" N="400"></L>
<L>And where &thorn;ou comyst, with gode chere</L>
<L>In halle or bowre, bydde "god be here!"</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou cast to no mannes dogge,</L>
<L N="24">With staff ne stone at hors ne hogge;</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou not scorne ne iape</L>
<L>No&thorn;er with man, maydyn, ne ape;</L>
<L>Lete no man of &thorn;ee make playnt;</L>
<L N="28">Swere &thorn;ou not by god no&thorn;er by saynt.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou be curteys stondyng at mete;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at men &yogh;euyth &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou take &amp; ete;</L>
<L>And loke that &thorn;ou nother crye ne crave,</L>
<L N="32">And say "that and that wold y have;"</L>
<L>But stond &thorn;ou stylle be-fore &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> borde,</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou speke no lowde worde.</L>
<L>And, chyld, wyrshep thy fader and thy moder,</L>
<L N="36">And loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou greve no&thorn;er on ne o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>But euer among &thorn;ou shalt knele adowne,</L>
<L>And aske here blessyng and here benesowne.</L>
<L>And, chyld, kepe thy clo&thorn;es fayre &amp; clene,</L>
<L N="40">And lete no fowle fylth on hem be sene.</L>
<L>Chyld, clem &thorn;ou not ouer hows ne walle</L>
<L>For no frute<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cp. Lydgate's Tricks at School, <I>Forewords,</I> p. xliv.</NOTE>, bryddes, ne balle;</L>
<L>And, chyld, cast no stonys ouer men hows,</L>
<L N="44">Ne cast no stonys at no glas wyndowys;</L>
<L>Ne make no crying, yapis, ne playes,</L>
<L>In holy chyrche on holy dayes.</L>
<L>And, chyld, y warne &thorn;ee of ano&thorn;er thynge,</L>
<L N="48">Kepe &thorn;ee fro many wordes and yangelyng.</L>
<L>And, chyld, whan &thorn;ou gost to play,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou come home by lyght of day.</L>
<L>And, chyld, I warne the of a-no&thorn;er mater,</L>
<L N="52">Loke &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;ee wel fro fyre and water;</L>
<L>And be ware and wyse how &thorn;at &thorn;ou lokys</L>
<L>Ouer any brynk, welle, or brokys;
<PB REF="00000561.tif" N="401"></L>
<L>And when &thorn;ou stondyst at any schate<NOTE PLACE="foot">? meaning. <I>Skathie,</I> a fence. Jamieson. <I>Skaith,</I> hurt, harm. Halliwell.</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="56">By ware and wyse &thorn;at &thorn;ou cacche no stake,</L>
<L>For meny chyld with-out drede</L>
<L>Ys dede or dysseyuyd throw ywell hede.<MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Chyld, kepe thy boke, cappe, and glouys,</L>
<L N="60">And al thyng &thorn;at &thorn;ee behouys;</L>
<L>And but &thorn;ou do, &thorn;ou shat fare the wors,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to be bete on &thorn;e bare ers.</L>
<L>Chyld, be &thorn;ou lyer no&thorn;er no theffe;</L>
<L N="64">Be &thorn;ou no mecher<NOTE PLACE="foot">A mychare seems to denote properly a sneaking thief. Way. Prompt., p. 336. <I>Mychare,</I> a covetous, sordid fellow. Jamieson. Fr. <I>pleure-pain:</I> m. A niggardlie wretch; a puling <I>micher</I> or miser. Cotgrave.</NOTE> for myscheffe.</L>
<L>Chyld, make &thorn;ou no mowys ne knakkes</L>
<L>Be-fore no men, ne by-hynd here bakkes,</L>
<L>But be of fayre semelaunt and contenaunce,</L>
<L N="68">For by fayre manerys men may &thorn;ee a-vaunce.</L>
<L>Chyld whan &thorn;ou gost yn eny strete,</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;ou eny gode man or woman mete,</L>
<L>Avale thy hode to hym or to here,</L>
<L N="72">And bydde, "god spede dame or sere!"</L>
<L>And be they smalle or grete,</L>
<L>This lesson &thorn;at &thorn;ou not for-gete,&mdash;</L>
<L>For hyt is semely to euery mannys chylde,&mdash;</L>
<L N="76">And namely to clerkes to be meke &amp; mylde.</L>
<L>And, chyld, ryse by tyme and go to scole,</L>
<L>And fare not as Wanton fole,</L>
<L>And lerne as fast as &thorn;ou may and can,</L>
<L N="80">For owre byschop is an old man,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-for &thorn;ou most lerne fast</L>
<L>Iff &thorn;ou wolt be bysshop when he is past.</L>
<L>Chyld, y bydde &thorn;e on my blessyng</L>
<L N="84">That &thorn;ou for-&yogh;ete nat &thorn;is for no thyng,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou loke, hold hyt wel on &thorn;y mynde,
<PB REF="00000562.tif" N="402"></L>
<L>For &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> best &thorn;u shalt hyt fynde;</L>
<L>For, as &thorn;e wyse man sayth and preuyth,</L>
<L N="88">A leve chyld, lore he be-houyth;</L>
<L>And as men sayth &thorn;at ben leryd,<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He hatyth &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chyld &thorn;at sparyth &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> rodde;</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e wyse man sayth yn his boke</L>
<L N="92">Off prouerbis and wysedomes, ho wol loke,</L>
<L>"As a sharppe spore makyth an hors to renne</L>
<L>Vnder a man that shold werre wynne,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t so a &yogh;erde may make a chyld</L>
<L N="96">To lerne welle hys lesson, and to be myld."</L>
<L>Lo, chyldryn, here may &yogh;e al here and se</L>
<L>How al chyldryn chastyd shold be;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor, chyldere, loke &thorn;at ye do well,</L>
<L N="100">And no harde betyng shall ye be-falle:</L>
<L>Thys may &yogh;e al be ryght gode men.</L>
<L>God graunt yow grace so to preferue yow.</L>
<TRAILER>Amen!</TRAILER>
<TRAILER>Symon.</TRAILER>
</LG>
